# nl-rag distilled facts — domain: chemical-energy
# one declarative sentence per line; load with:  neuron --db app.db import pack.facts --scope knowledge
[src:chemical-energy/airborne-wind-energy] The term high-altitude wind power (HAWP) has been used to refer to AWE systems.
[src:chemical-energy/airborne-wind-energy] However, semantically HAWP might also include wind energy conversion systems that are somehow positioned at a large height from the ground or sea surface.
[src:chemical-energy/airborne-wind-energy] Various mechanisms are proposed for capturing the kinetic energy of winds such as kites, kytoons, aerostats, gliders, gliders with turbines for regenerative soaring, sailplanes with turbines, or other airfoils, including multiple-point building- or terrain-enabled holdings.
[src:chemical-energy/airborne-wind-energy] Once the mechanical energy is derived from the wind's kinetic energy, then many options are available for using that mechanical energy: direct traction, conversion to electricity aloft or at ground station, conversion to laser or microwave for power beaming to other aircraft or ground receivers.
[src:chemical-energy/airborne-wind-energy] Winds at higher altitudes become steadier, more persistent, and of higher velocity.
[src:chemical-energy/airborne-wind-energy] Because power available in wind increases as the cube of velocity (the velocity-cubed law), assuming other parameters remaining the same, doubling a wind's velocity gives 23=8 times the power; tripling the velocity gives 33=27 times the available power.
[src:chemical-energy/airborne-wind-energy] With steadier and more predictable winds, high-altitude wind has an advantage over wind near the ground.
[src:chemical-energy/airborne-wind-energy] Being able to locate HAWP to effective altitudes and using the vertical dimension of airspace for wind farming brings further advantage using high-altitude winds for generating energy.
[src:chemical-energy/airborne-wind-energy] High-altitude wind generators can be adjusted in height and position to maximize energy return, which is impractical with fixed tower-mounted wind generators.
[src:chemical-energy/airborne-wind-energy] In each range of altitudes there are altitude-specific concerns being addressed by researchers and developers.
[src:chemical-energy/airborne-wind-energy] As altitude increases, tethers increase in length, the temperature of the air changes, and vulnerability to atmospheric lightning changes.
[src:chemical-energy/airborne-wind-energy] With increasing altitude, exposure to liabilities increase, costs increase, turbulence exposure changes, likelihood of having the system fly in more than one directional strata of winds increases, and the costs of operation changes.
[src:chemical-energy/airborne-wind-energy] HAWP systems that are flown must climb through all intermediate altitudes up to final working altitudes—being at first a low- and then a high- altitude device.
[src:chemical-energy/airborne-wind-energy] An atlas of the high-altitude wind power resource has been prepared for all points on Earth.
[src:chemical-energy/airborne-wind-energy] A similar atlas of global assessment was developed at Joby Energy.
[src:chemical-energy/airborne-wind-energy] When a scheme's purpose is to propel ships and boats, the objects tether-placed in the wind will tend to have most of the captured energy be in useful tension in the main tether.
[src:chemical-energy/airborne-wind-energy] The aloft working bodies will be operated to maintain useful tension even while the ship is moving.
[src:chemical-energy/airborne-wind-energy] This is the method for powerkiting sports.
[src:chemical-energy/airborne-wind-energy] This sector of HAWP is the most installed method.
[src:chemical-energy/airborne-wind-energy] Folklore suggests that Benjamin Franklin used the traction method of HAWP.
[src:chemical-energy/airborne-wind-energy] George Pocock was a pioneer in tugging vehicles by traction.
[src:chemical-energy/airborne-wind-energy] Solutions in built systems have control mechanisms variously situated.
[src:chemical-energy/airborne-wind-energy] Some systems are passive, or active, or a mix.
[src:chemical-energy/airborne-wind-energy] When a kite steering unit (KSU) is lofted, the KSU may be robotic and self-contained; a KSU may be operated from the ground via radio-control by a live human operator or by smart computer programs.
[src:chemical-energy/airborne-wind-energy] Some systems have built sensors in the aircraft body that report parameters like position, relative position to other parts.
[src:chemical-energy/airborne-wind-energy] Kite control units (KCU) have involved more than steering; tether reeling speeds and directions can be adjusted in response to tether tensions and needs of the system during a power-generating phase or return-non-power-generating phase.
[src:chemical-energy/airborne-wind-energy] The mechanical energy of the device may be converted to heat, sound, electricity, light, tension, pushes, pulls, laser, microwave, chemical changes, or compression of gases.
[src:chemical-energy/airborne-wind-energy] Traction is a big direct use of the mechanical energy as in tugging cargo ships and kiteboarders.
[src:chemical-energy/airborne-wind-energy] There are several methods of getting the mechanical energy from the wind's kinetic energy.
[src:chemical-energy/airborne-wind-energy] Lighter-than-air (LTA) moored aerostats are employed as lifters of turbines.
[src:chemical-energy/airborne-wind-energy] Heavier-than-air (HTA) tethered airfoils are being used as lifters or turbines themselves.
[src:chemical-energy/airborne-wind-energy] Combinations of LTA and HTA devices in one system are being built and flown to capture HAWP.
[src:chemical-energy/airborne-wind-energy] Even a family of free-flight airborne devices are represented in the literature that capture the kinetic energy of high-altitude winds (beginning with a description in 1967 by Richard Miller in his book *Without Visible Means of Support*) and a contemporary patent application by Dale C.
[src:chemical-energy/airborne-wind-energy] Kramer, soaring sailplane competitor, inventor.
[src:chemical-energy/airborne-wind-energy] A research on airborne wind turbine technology innovations reveals that the “Kite type AWTs” technique, the most common type, has high scope of growth in the future; it has contributed for about 44% of the total airborne wind energy during 2008–2012.
[src:chemical-energy/airborne-wind-energy] The kite type AWTs extract energy through wind turbines suspended at high altitudes using kites such as multi-tethered kite, kite and dual purpose circular fan, rotary wing kites etc.
[src:chemical-energy/airborne-wind-energy] Electricity generation is just one of the options for capturing mechanical energy; however, this option dominates the focus of professionals aiming to supply large amounts of energy to commerce and utilities.
[src:chemical-energy/airborne-wind-energy] A long array of secondary options include tugging water turbines, pumping of water, or compressing air or hydrogen.
[src:chemical-energy/airborne-wind-energy] The position of the electric generator is a distinguishing feature among systems.
[src:chemical-energy/airborne-wind-energy] Flying the generator aloft is done in a variety of ways.
[src:chemical-energy/airborne-wind-energy] Keeping the generator at the mooring region is another large design option.
[src:chemical-energy/airborne-wind-energy] The option in one system of a generator aloft and at the ground station has been used where a small generator operates electronic devices aloft while the ground generator is the big worker to make electricity for significant loads.
[src:chemical-energy/airborne-wind-energy] The “Carousel” configuration several kites fly at a constant height and higher altitudes, pulling in rotation a generator that moves on a wide circular rail.
[src:chemical-energy/airborne-wind-energy] For a large Carousel system, the power obtained can be calculated as of the order of GW, exposing a law that see the power attainable as a function of the diameter raised to the fifth power, while the increment of cost of the generator is linear.
[src:chemical-energy/airborne-wind-energy] One method of keeping working HAWP systems aloft is to use buoyant aerostats whether or not the electric generator is lifted or left on the ground.
[src:chemical-energy/airborne-wind-energy] The aerostats are usually, but not always, shaped to achieve a kiting lifting effect.
[src:chemical-energy/airborne-wind-energy] Recharging leaked lifting gas receives various solutions.
[src:chemical-energy/airborne-wind-energy] In case of productive winds the aerostats are typically blown down by the aerodynamic drag applied on the wide and unavoidable Reynolds surface excluding them de facto from the HAWP category.
[src:chemical-energy/airborne-wind-energy] Conceptually, two adjacent mountains (natural or terrain-enabled) or artificial buildings or towers (urban or artificial) could have a wind turbine suspended between them by use of cables.
[src:chemical-energy/airborne-wind-energy] When HAWP is cabled between two mountain tops across a valley, the HAWP device is not airborne, but borne up by the cable system.
[src:chemical-energy/airborne-wind-energy] No such systems are known to be in use, though patents teach these methods.
[src:chemical-energy/airborne-wind-energy] When non-cabled bridges are the foundation for holding wind turbines high above the ground, then these are grouped with conventional towered turbines and are outside the intent of HAWP where the tethering an airborne system is foundational.
[src:chemical-energy/airborne-wind-energy] Lightning, aircraft traffic, emergency procedures, system inspections, visibility marking of system parts and its tethers, electrical safety, runaway-wing procedures, over-powering controls, appropriate mooring, and more form the safety environment for HAWP systems.
[src:chemical-energy/airborne-wind-energy] There have been several periods of high interest in HAWP before the contemporary activity.
[src:chemical-energy/airborne-wind-energy] The first period had a high focus on pulling carriages over the lands and capturing atmospheric electricity and lightning for human use.
[src:chemical-energy/airborne-wind-energy] The second period was in the 1970s and 1980s when research and investment flourished; a drop in oil price resulted in no significant installations of HAWP.
[src:chemical-energy/airborne-wind-energy] Return on investment (ROI) has been the key parameter; that ROI remains in focus in the current development activity while in the background is the renewable and sustainable energy movement supporting wind power of any kind; but HAWP must compete on ROI with conventional towered solutions.
[src:chemical-energy/airborne-wind-energy] A test center at Lista, Norway provides independent verification of research.
[src:chemical-energy/airborne-wind-energy] Early centuries of kiting demonstrated that the kite is a rotary engine that rotates its tether part about its mooring point and causes hands and arms to move because of the energy captured from higher winds into the mechanical device.
[src:chemical-energy/airborne-wind-energy] The tension in the lofted devices performs the work of lifting and pulling body parts and things.
[src:chemical-energy/airborne-wind-energy] Airborne wind energy (AWE) for HAWP was birthed thousands of years ago; naming what happened and developing the implied potentials of tethered aircraft for doing special works is what is occurring in AWE HAWP.
[src:chemical-energy/airborne-wind-energy] What is "low" for some workers is "high" for others.
[src:chemical-energy/airborne-wind-energy] Autorotation is the basis of a large sector of AWE technology.
[src:chemical-energy/binding-energy] In physics and chemistry, **binding energy** is the smallest amount of energy required to remove a particle from a system of particles or to disassemble a system of particles into individual parts.
[src:chemical-energy/binding-energy] In the former meaning the term is predominantly used in condensed matter physics, atomic physics, and chemistry, whereas in nuclear physics the term *separation energy* is used.
[src:chemical-energy/binding-energy] A bound system is typically at a lower energy level than its unbound constituents.
[src:chemical-energy/binding-energy] According to relativity theory, a Δ*E* decrease in the total energy of a system is accompanied by a decrease Δ*m* in the total mass, where Δ*mc*2 = Δ*E*.
[src:chemical-energy/binding-energy] There are several types of binding energy, each operating over a different distance and energy scale.
[src:chemical-energy/binding-energy] The smaller the size of a bound system, the higher its associated binding energy.
[src:chemical-energy/binding-energy] A bound system is typically at a lower energy level than its unbound constituents because its mass must be less than the total mass of its unbound constituents.
[src:chemical-energy/binding-energy] For systems with low binding energies, this "lost" mass after binding may be fractionally small, whereas for systems with high binding energies, the missing mass may be an easily measurable fraction.
[src:chemical-energy/binding-energy] This missing mass may be lost during the process of binding as energy in the form of heat or light, with the removed energy corresponding to the removed mass through Einstein's equation *E* = *mc*2.
[src:chemical-energy/binding-energy] In the process of binding, the constituents of the system might enter higher energy states of the nucleus/atom/molecule while retaining their mass, and because of this, it is necessary that they are removed from the system before its mass can decrease.
[src:chemical-energy/binding-energy] Once the system cools to normal temperatures and returns to ground states regarding energy levels, it will contain less mass than when it first combined and was at high energy.
[src:chemical-energy/binding-energy] This loss of heat represents the "mass deficit", and the heat itself retains the mass that was lost (from the point of view of the initial system).
[src:chemical-energy/binding-energy] This mass will appear in any other system that absorbs the heat and gains thermal energy.
[src:chemical-energy/binding-energy] For example, if two objects are attracting each other in space through their gravitational field, the attraction force accelerates the objects, increasing their velocity, which converts their potential energy (gravity) into kinetic energy.
[src:chemical-energy/binding-energy] When the particles either pass through each other without interaction or elastically repel during the collision, the gained kinetic energy (related to speed) begins to revert into potential energy, driving the collided particles apart.
[src:chemical-energy/binding-energy] The decelerating particles will return to the initial distance and beyond into infinity, or stop and repeat the collision (oscillation takes place).
[src:chemical-energy/binding-energy] This shows that the system, which loses no energy, does not combine (bind) into a solid object, parts of which oscillate at short distances.
[src:chemical-energy/binding-energy] Therefore, to bind the particles, the kinetic energy gained due to the attraction must be dissipated by resistive force.
[src:chemical-energy/binding-energy] Complex objects in collision ordinarily undergo inelastic collision, transforming some kinetic energy into internal energy (heat content, which is atomic movement), which is further radiated in the form of photons – the light and heat.
[src:chemical-energy/binding-energy] Once the energy to escape the gravity is dissipated in the collision, the parts will oscillate at a closer, possibly atomic, distance, thus looking like one solid object.
[src:chemical-energy/binding-energy] This lost energy, necessary to overcome the potential barrier to separate the objects, is the binding energy.
[src:chemical-energy/binding-energy] If this binding energy were retained in the system as heat, its mass would not decrease, whereas binding energy lost from the system as heat radiation would itself have mass.
[src:chemical-energy/binding-energy] It directly represents the "mass deficit" of the cold, bound system.
[src:chemical-energy/binding-energy] Closely analogous considerations apply in chemical and nuclear reactions.
[src:chemical-energy/binding-energy] Exothermic chemical reactions in closed systems do not change mass, but do become less massive once the heat of reaction is removed, though this mass change is too small to measure with standard equipment.
[src:chemical-energy/binding-energy] In nuclear reactions, the fraction of mass that may be removed as light or heat, i.e. binding energy, is often a much larger fraction of the system mass.
[src:chemical-energy/binding-energy] It may thus be measured directly as a mass difference between rest masses of reactants and (cooled) products.
[src:chemical-energy/binding-energy] This is because nuclear forces are comparatively stronger than the Coulombic forces associated with the interactions between electrons and protons that generate heat in chemistry.
[src:chemical-energy/binding-energy] Mass change (decrease) in bound systems, particularly atomic nuclei, has also been termed *mass defect*, *mass deficit*, or mass *packing fraction*.
[src:chemical-energy/binding-energy] The difference between the unbound system calculated mass and experimentally measured mass of nucleus (mass change) is denoted as Δ*m*.
[src:chemical-energy/binding-energy] After a nuclear reaction occurs that results in an excited nucleus, the energy that must be radiated or otherwise removed as binding energy in order to decay to the unexcited state may be in one of several forms.
[src:chemical-energy/binding-energy] This may be electromagnetic waves, such as gamma radiation; the kinetic energy of an ejected particle, such as an electron, in internal conversion decay; or partly as the rest mass of one or more emitted particles, such as the particles of beta decay.
[src:chemical-energy/binding-energy] No mass deficit can appear, in theory, until this radiation or this energy has been emitted and is no longer part of the system.
[src:chemical-energy/binding-energy] When nucleons bind together to form a nucleus, they must lose a small amount of mass, i.e. there is a change in mass to stay bound.
[src:chemical-energy/binding-energy] This mass change must be released as various types of photon or other particle energy as above, according to the relation *E* = *mc*2.
[src:chemical-energy/binding-energy] Thus, after the binding energy has been removed, **binding energy = mass change × *c*2**.
[src:chemical-energy/binding-energy] This energy is a measure of the forces that hold the nucleons together.
[src:chemical-energy/binding-energy] It represents energy that must be resupplied from the environment for the nucleus to be broken up into individual nucleons.
[src:chemical-energy/binding-energy] For example, an atom of deuterium has a mass defect of 0.0023884 Da, and its binding energy is nearly equal to 2.23 MeV.
[src:chemical-energy/binding-energy] This means that energy of 2.23 MeV is required to disintegrate an atom of deuterium.
[src:chemical-energy/binding-energy] The energy given off during either nuclear fusion or nuclear fission is the difference of the binding energies of the "fuel", i.e. the initial nuclide(s), from that of the fission or fusion products.
[src:chemical-energy/binding-energy] In practice, this energy may also be calculated from the substantial mass differences between the fuel and products, which uses previous measurements of the atomic masses of known nuclides, which always have the same mass for each species.
[src:chemical-energy/binding-energy] This mass difference appears once evolved heat and radiation have been removed, which is required for measuring the (rest) masses of the (non-excited) nuclides involved in such calculations.
[src:chemical-energy/bioenergy] Bioenergy can help with climate change mitigation but in some cases the required biomass production can increase greenhouse gas emissions or lead to local biodiversity loss.
[src:chemical-energy/bioenergy] The environmental impacts of biomass production can be problematic, depending on how the biomass is produced and harvested.
[src:chemical-energy/bioenergy] But it still produces CO2; so long as the energy is derived from breaking chemical bonds.
[src:chemical-energy/bioenergy] The IEA's Net Zero by 2050 scenario calls for traditional bioenergy to be phased out by 2030, with modern bioenergy's share increasing from 6.6% in 2020 to 13.1% in 2030 and 18.7% in 2050.
[src:chemical-energy/bioenergy] Bioenergy has a significant climate change mitigation potential if implemented correctly.
[src:chemical-energy/bioenergy] Most of the recommended pathways to limit global warming include substantial contributions from bioenergy in 2050 (average at 200 EJ).
[src:chemical-energy/bioenergy] The IPCC Sixth Assessment Report defines *bioenergy* as "energy derived from any form of biomass or its metabolic by-products".
[src:chemical-energy/bioenergy] It goes on to define *biomass* in this context as "organic material excluding the material that is fossilised or embedded in geological formations".
[src:chemical-energy/bioenergy] This means that coal or other fossil fuels is not a form of biomass in this context.
[src:chemical-energy/bioenergy] The term *traditional biomass* for bioenergy means "the combustion of wood, charcoal, agricultural residues and/or animal dung for cooking or heating in open fires or in inefficient stoves as is common in low-income countries".
[src:chemical-energy/bioenergy] Since biomass can also be used as a fuel directly (e.g. wood logs), the terms *biomass* and *biofuel* have sometimes been used interchangeably.
[src:chemical-energy/bioenergy] However, the term *biomass* usually denotes the biological raw material the fuel is made of.
[src:chemical-energy/bioenergy] The terms biofuel or biogas are generally reserved for liquid or gaseous fuels respectively.
[src:chemical-energy/bioenergy] Wood and wood residues is the largest biomass energy source today.
[src:chemical-energy/bioenergy] Wood can be used as a fuel directly or processed into pellet fuel or other forms of fuels.
[src:chemical-energy/bioenergy] Other plants can also be used as fuel, for instance maize, switchgrass, miscanthus and bamboo.
[src:chemical-energy/bioenergy] The main waste feedstocks are wood waste, agricultural waste, municipal solid waste, and manufacturing waste.
[src:chemical-energy/bioenergy] Many **chemical conversions** are based on established coal-based processes, such as the Fischer-Tropsch synthesis.
[src:chemical-energy/bioenergy] Like coal, biomass can be converted into multiple commodity chemicals.
[src:chemical-energy/bioenergy] Biomass heating systems generate heat from biomass.
[src:chemical-energy/bioenergy] The systems may use direct combustion, gasification, combined heat and power (CHP), anaerobic digestion or aerobic digestion to produce heat.
[src:chemical-energy/bioenergy] Biomass heating may be fully automated or semi-automated they may be pellet-fired, or they may be combined heat and power systems .
[src:chemical-energy/bioenergy] First-generation (or "conventional") biofuels are made from *food* sources grown on arable lands, such as sugarcane and maize.
[src:chemical-energy/bioenergy] Sugars present in this biomass are fermented to produce bioethanol, an alcohol fuel which serves as an additive to gasoline, or in a fuel cell to produce electricity.
[src:chemical-energy/bioenergy] Bioethanol is made by fermentation, mostly from carbohydrates produced in sugar or starch crops such as corn, sugarcane, or sweet sorghum.
[src:chemical-energy/bioenergy] Bioethanol is widely used in the United States and in Brazil.
[src:chemical-energy/bioenergy] Biodiesel is produced from the oils in for instance rapeseed or sugar beets and is the most common biofuel in Europe.
[src:chemical-energy/bioenergy] Second-generation biofuels (also called "advanced biofuels") utilize *non-food*-based biomass sources such as perennial energy crops and agricultural residues/waste.
[src:chemical-energy/bioenergy] The feedstock used to make the fuels either grow on arable land but are byproducts of the main crop, or they are grown on marginal land.
[src:chemical-energy/bioenergy] Waste from industry, agriculture, forestry and households can also be used for second-generation biofuels, using e.g. anaerobic digestion to produce biogas, gasification to produce syngas or by direct combustion.
[src:chemical-energy/bioenergy] Cellulosic biomass, derived from non-food sources, such as trees and grasses, is being developed as a feedstock for ethanol production, and biodiesel can be produced from left-over food products like vegetable oils and animal fats.
[src:chemical-energy/bioenergy] The surface power production densities of a crop will determine how much land is required for production.
[src:chemical-energy/bioenergy] The average lifecycle surface power densities for biomass, wind, hydro and solar power production are 0.30 W/m2, 1 W/m2, 3 W/m2 and 5 W/m2, respectively (power in the form of heat for biomass, and electricity for wind, hydro and solar).
[src:chemical-energy/bioenergy] Lifecycle surface power density includes land used by all supporting infrastructure, manufacturing, mining/harvesting and decommissioning.
[src:chemical-energy/bioenergy] Another estimate puts the values at 0.08 W/m2 for biomass, 0.14 W/m2 for hydro, 1.84 W/m2 for wind, and 6.63 W/m2 for solar (median values, with none of the renewable sources exceeding 10 W/m2).
[src:chemical-energy/bioenergy] Carbon capture and storage technology can be used to capture emissions from bioenergy power plants.
[src:chemical-energy/bioenergy] This process is known as bioenergy with carbon capture and storage (BECCS) and can result in net carbon dioxide removal from the atmosphere.
[src:chemical-energy/bioenergy] However, BECCS can also result in net positive emissions depending on how the biomass material is grown, harvested, and transported.
[src:chemical-energy/bioenergy] Deployment of BECCS at scales described in some climate change mitigation pathways would require converting large amounts of cropland.
[src:chemical-energy/bioenergy] Bioenergy with carbon capture and storage (BECCS) is the process of extracting bioenergy from biomass and capturing and storing the carbon dioxide (CO2) that is produced.
[src:chemical-energy/bioenergy] Greenhouse gas emissions from bioenergy can be low because when vegetation is harvested for bioenergy, new vegetation can grow that will absorb CO2 from the air through photosynthesis.
[src:chemical-energy/bioenergy] After the biomass is harvested, energy ("bioenergy") is extracted in useful forms (electricity, heat, biofuels, etc.) as the biomass is utilized through combustion, fermentation, pyrolysis or other conversion methods.
[src:chemical-energy/bioenergy] In BECCS, some of the CO2 is captured before it enters the atmosphere, and stored underground using carbon capture and storage technology.
[src:chemical-energy/bioenergy] Under some conditions, BECCS can remove carbon dioxide from the atmosphere.
[src:chemical-energy/bioenergy] The potential range of negative emissions from BECCS was estimated to be zero to 22 giga tonnes per year.
[src:chemical-energy/bioenergy] As of 2024, there are large-scale 3 BECCS projects operating in the world.
[src:chemical-energy/bioenergy] Wide deployment of BECCS is constrained by cost and availability of biomass.
[src:chemical-energy/bioenergy] Since biomass production is land-intensive, deployment of BECCS can pose major risks to food production, human rights, and biodiversity.
[src:chemical-energy/bioenergy] The climate impact of bioenergy varies considerably depending on where biomass feedstocks come from and how they are grown.
[src:chemical-energy/bioenergy] For example, burning wood for energy releases carbon dioxide; those emissions can be significantly offset if the trees that were harvested are replaced by new trees in a well-managed forest, as the new trees will absorb carbon dioxide from the air as they grow.
[src:chemical-energy/bioenergy] However, the establishment and cultivation of bioenergy crops can displace natural ecosystems, degrade soils, and consume water resources and synthetic fertilisers.
[src:chemical-energy/bioenergy] Approximately one-third of all wood used for traditional heating and cooking in tropical areas is harvested unsustainably.
[src:chemical-energy/bioenergy] Bioenergy feedstocks typically require significant amounts of energy to harvest, dry, and transport; the energy usage for these processes may emit greenhouse gases.
[src:chemical-energy/bioenergy] In some cases, the impacts of land-use change, cultivation, and processing can result in higher overall carbon emissions for bioenergy compared to using fossil fuels.
[src:chemical-energy/bioenergy] Use of farmland for growing biomass can result in less land being available for growing food.
[src:chemical-energy/bioenergy] In the United States, around 10% of motor gasoline has been replaced by corn-based ethanol, which requires a significant proportion of the harvest.
[src:chemical-energy/bioenergy] In Malaysia and Indonesia, clearing forests to produce palm oil for biodiesel has led to serious social and environmental effects, as these forests are critical carbon sinks and habitats for diverse species.
[src:chemical-energy/bioenergy] Since photosynthesis captures only a small fraction of the energy in sunlight, producing a given amount of bioenergy requires a large amount of land compared to other renewable energy sources.
[src:chemical-energy/bioenergy] Bioenergy can either mitigate (i.e. reduce) or increase greenhouse gas emissions.
[src:chemical-energy/bioenergy] Local environmental impacts can be problematic.
[src:chemical-energy/bioenergy] For example, forests are sometimes cleared for the production of sugarcane-derived bioethanol, like in the case of a large-scale project in Indonesia in 2025.
[src:chemical-energy/bioenergy] Biomass production can create significant social and environmental pressure in the locations where the biomass is produced.
[src:chemical-energy/bioenergy] The impact is primarily related to the low surface power density of biomass.
[src:chemical-energy/bioenergy] The low surface power density has the effect that much larger land areas are needed in order to produce the same amount of energy, compared to for instance fossil fuels.
[src:chemical-energy/bioenergy] Long-distance transport of biomass have been criticised as wasteful and unsustainable, and there have been protests against forest biomass export in Sweden and Canada.
[src:chemical-energy/bioenergy] In 2020 bioenergy produced 58 EJ (exajoules) of energy, compared to 172 EJ from crude oil, 157 EJ from coal, 138 EJ from natural gas, 29 EJ from nuclear, 16 EJ from hydro and 15 EJ from wind, solar and geothermal combined.
[src:chemical-energy/bioenergy] Most of the global bioenergy is produced from forest resources.
[src:chemical-energy/bioenergy] Generally, bioenergy expansion fell by 50% in 2020.
[src:chemical-energy/bioenergy] China and Europe are the only two regions that reported significant expansion in 2020, adding 2 GW and 1.2 GW of bioenergy capacity, respectively.
[src:chemical-energy/bioenergy] Almost all available sawmill residue is already being utilized for pellet production, so there is no room for expansion.
[src:chemical-energy/bioenergy] For the bioenergy sector to significantly expand in the future, more of the harvested pulpwood must go to pellet mills.
[src:chemical-energy/bioenergy] However, the harvest of pulpwood (tree thinnings) removes the possibility for these trees to grow old and therefore maximize their carbon holding capacity.
[src:chemical-energy/bioenergy] Compared to pulpwood, sawmill residues have lower net emissions: "Some types of biomass feedstock can be carbon-neutral, at least over a period of a few years, including in particular sawmill residues.
[src:chemical-energy/biomass] The composition of a specific source of biomass depends on whether it is derived from plants, animals, microorganisms, or some mixture of all biological matter.
[src:chemical-energy/biomass] Biomass may also contain material from non-biological origin, due to contamination from anthropogenic activities.
[src:chemical-energy/biomass] The table below summarizes the main types of biomasses and their typical sources.
[src:chemical-energy/biomass] The composition of biomass on a chemical level is determined by whether it is plant or animal matter.
[src:chemical-energy/biomass] Biomass is a form of renewable energy useful as fuel and as a source of some chemical products.
[src:chemical-energy/biomass] Relative to coal and petroleum however, the energy content of biomass is low.
[src:chemical-energy/biomass] Compared to traditional fossil fuels, biomass has a high oxygen content.
[src:chemical-energy/biomass] Its carbon is partially combusted, so to speak.
[src:chemical-energy/biomass] One such notable example is the production of bio-ethanol.
[src:chemical-energy/biomass] There is a general classification of biomass that is produced or sourced for conversion processes.
[src:chemical-energy/biomass] Biofuels such as bioethanol and biodiesel, and bioplastics, are typically derived from primary or “first-generation” source energy-dense plants and oils such as rapeseed, sugarcane, or corn.
[src:chemical-energy/biomass] Their high content of sugars and oils makes them ideal as feedstocks, however, there are drawbacks to their use.
[src:chemical-energy/biomass] As well as inflating the price of the chosen crop due to increased demand, arable land that would otherwise be used to grow food for human and animal consumption is rendered unavailable.
[src:chemical-energy/biomass] Secondary or “second-generation” source biomass encompasses a much wider variety of plant and animal matter.
[src:chemical-energy/biomass] It may be derived from a relatively pure source, such as wood chippings or grass, or it may be a less well defined solid waste stream.
[src:chemical-energy/biomass] This type of biomass is far more challenging to work with, as it contains a more varied mixture of compounds that cannot be easily converted into useful products.
[src:chemical-energy/biomass] Despite this, there continues to be intensive research and industry interest in second-generation biomass conversion processes due to its potential to re-use potentially valuable products and derivative products that would otherwise be wasted by incineration.
[src:chemical-energy/biomass] In ecological studies, biomass refers to the total amount of biological organisms that are present in a given environment or ecosystem.
[src:chemical-energy/biomass] It may encompass the entirety of biological matter, or a subset of species or individuals.
[src:chemical-energy/biomass] It is typically expressed as the total weight of carbon that is contained within the chosen group of organisms.
[src:chemical-energy/biomass] A 2017 estimate of the total amount of biomass within the biosphere is approximately 550 gigatons of carbon, with a significant majority of this being terrestrial plants (approx.
[src:chemical-energy/biomass] To calculate that, remote sensing techniques such as the Normalized difference vegetation index (NDVI), is commonly used to estimate biomass over large scales.
[src:chemical-energy/bond-energy] In chemistry, **bond energy** (*BE*) is one measure of the strength of a chemical bond.
[src:chemical-energy/bond-energy] It is sometimes called the **mean bond**, **bond enthalpy**, **average bond enthalpy**, or **bond strength**.
[src:chemical-energy/bond-energy] IUPAC defines bond energy as the average value of the gas-phase bond-dissociation energy (usually at a temperature of 298.15 K) for all bonds of the same type within the same chemical species.
[src:chemical-energy/bond-energy] The bond dissociation energy (enthalpy) is also referred to as bond disruption energy, bond energy, bond strength, or binding energy (abbreviation: *BDE*, *BE*, or *D*).
[src:chemical-energy/bond-energy] It is defined as the standard enthalpy change of the following fission: R—*X* → R + *X*.
[src:chemical-energy/bond-energy] This equation tells us that the *BDE* for a given bond is equal to the energy of the individual components that make up the bond when they are free and unbonded minus the energy of the components when they are bonded together.
[src:chemical-energy/bond-energy] These energies are given by the enthalpy of formation Δ*Hf*º of the components in each state.
[src:chemical-energy/bond-energy] The enthalpy of formation of a large number of atoms, free radicals, ions, clusters and compounds is available from the websites of NIST, NASA, CODATA, and IUPAC.
[src:chemical-energy/bond-energy] Most authors use the *BDE* values at 298.15 K.
[src:chemical-energy/bond-energy] For example, the carbon–hydrogen bond energy in methane *BE*(C–H) is the enthalpy change (∆*H*) of breaking one molecule of methane into a carbon atom and four hydrogen radicals, divided by four.
[src:chemical-energy/bond-energy] The exact value for a certain pair of bonded elements varies somewhat depending on the specific molecule, so tabulated bond energies are generally averages from a number of selected typical chemical species containing that type of bond.
[src:chemical-energy/bond-energy] Bond energy (*BE*) is the average of all bond-dissociation energies of a single type of bond in a given molecule.
[src:chemical-energy/bond-energy] The bond-dissociation energies of several different bonds of the same type can vary even within a single molecule.
[src:chemical-energy/bond-energy] For example, a water molecule is composed of two O–H bonds bonded as H–O–H.
[src:chemical-energy/bond-energy] Although the two bonds are the equivalent in the original symmetric molecule, the bond-dissociation energy of an oxygen–hydrogen bond varies slightly depending on whether or not there is another hydrogen atom bonded to the oxygen atom.
[src:chemical-energy/bond-energy] Thus, the bond energy of a molecule of water is 461.5 kJ/mol (110.3 kcal/mol).
[src:chemical-energy/bond-energy] When the bond is broken, the bonding electron pair will split equally to the products.
[src:chemical-energy/bond-energy] This process is called homolytic bond cleavage (homolytic cleavage; homolysis) and results in the formation of radicals.
[src:chemical-energy/bond-energy] The strength of a bond can be estimated by comparing the atomic radii of the atoms that form the bond to the length of bond itself.
[src:chemical-energy/bond-energy] For example, the atomic radius of boron is estimated at 85 pm, while the length of the B–B bond in Diboron tetrachloride, B2Cl4 is 175 pm.
[src:chemical-energy/bond-energy] This ratio is slightly larger than 1, indicating that the bond itself is slightly longer than the expected minimum overlap between the two boron atoms' valence electron clouds.
[src:chemical-energy/bond-energy] Thus, we can conclude that this bond is a rather weak single bond.
[src:chemical-energy/bond-energy] In another example, the atomic radius of rhenium is 135 pm, with a Re–Re bond length of 224 pm in the compound [Re2Cl8]−2.
[src:chemical-energy/bond-energy] This ratio is notably lower than 1, indicating that there is a large amount of overlap between the valence electron clouds of the two rhenium atoms.
[src:chemical-energy/bond-energy] From this data, we can conclude that this is a very strong bond.
[src:chemical-energy/bond-energy] Experimentally, the Re-Re bond in [Re2Cl8]−2 was found to be a quadruple bond.
[src:chemical-energy/bond-energy] This method of determination is most useful for covalently bonded compounds.
[src:chemical-energy/bond-energy] In ionic compounds, the electronegativity of the two atoms bonding together has a major effect on their bond energy.
[src:chemical-energy/bond-energy] The extent of this effect is described by the compound's lattice energy, where a more negative lattice energy corresponds to a stronger force of attraction between the ions.
[src:chemical-energy/bond-energy] Generally, greater differences in electronegativity correspond to stronger ionic bonds.
[src:chemical-energy/bond-energy] For example, the compound sodium chloride (NaCl) has a lattice energy of −786 kJ/mol with an electronegativity difference of 2.23 between sodium and chlorine.
[src:chemical-energy/bond-energy] Meanwhile, the compound sodium iodide (NaI) has a lower lattice energy of −704 kJ/mol with a similarly lower electronegativity difference of 1.73 between sodium and iodine.
[src:chemical-energy/calorimeter] A **calorimeter** is a device used for calorimetry, or the process of measuring the heat of chemical reactions or physical changes as well as heat capacity.
[src:chemical-energy/calorimeter] Differential scanning calorimeters, isothermal micro calorimeters, titration calorimeters and accelerated rate calorimeters are among the most common types.
[src:chemical-energy/calorimeter] A simple calorimeter just consists of a thermometer attached to a metal container full of water suspended above a combustion chamber.
[src:chemical-energy/calorimeter] It is one of the measurement devices used in the study of thermodynamics, chemistry, and biochemistry.
[src:chemical-energy/calorimeter] To find the enthalpy change per mole of a substance A in a reaction between two substances A and B , the substances are separately added to a calorimeter and the initial and final temperatures (before the reaction has started and after it has finished) are noted.
[src:chemical-energy/calorimeter] Multiplying the temperature change by the mass and specific heat capacities of the substances gives a value for the energy given off or absorbed during the reaction.
[src:chemical-energy/calorimeter] In 1761 Joseph Black introduced the idea of latent heat which led to the creation of the first ice calorimeters.
[src:chemical-energy/calorimeter] In 1780, Antoine Lavoisier used the heat released by the respiration of a guinea pig to melt snow surrounding his apparatus, showing that respiratory gas exchange is a form of combustion, similar to the burning of a candle.
[src:chemical-energy/calorimeter] Lavoisier named this apparatus "calorimeter", based on both Greek and Latin roots.
[src:chemical-energy/calorimeter] One of the first ice calorimeters was used in the winter of 1782–83 by Lavoisier and Pierre-Simon Laplace.
[src:chemical-energy/calorimeter] It relied on the heat required for the melting of ice to measure the heat released in various chemical reactions.
[src:chemical-energy/calorimeter] An adiabatic calorimeter is a calorimeter used to examine a runaway reaction.
[src:chemical-energy/calorimeter] Since the calorimeter runs in an adiabatic environment, any heat generated by the material sample under test causes the sample to increase in temperature, thus fueling the reaction.
[src:chemical-energy/calorimeter] No adiabatic calorimeter is fully adiabatic – some heat will be lost by the sample to the sample holder.
[src:chemical-energy/calorimeter] A mathematical correction factor, known as the phi-factor, can be used to adjust the calorimetric result to account for these heat losses.
[src:chemical-energy/calorimeter] The phi-factor is the ratio of the thermal mass of the sample and sample holder to the thermal mass of the sample alone.
[src:chemical-energy/calorimeter] A reaction calorimeter is a calorimeter in which a chemical reaction is initiated within a closed insulated container.
[src:chemical-energy/calorimeter] Reaction heats are measured and the total heat is obtained by integrating heat flow versus time.
[src:chemical-energy/calorimeter] This is the standard used in industry to measure heats since industrial processes are engineered to run at constant temperatures.Reaction calorimetry can also be used to determine maximum heat release rate for chemical process engineering and for tracking the global kinetics of reactions.
[src:chemical-energy/calorimeter] The cooling/heating jacket controls either the temperature of the process or the temperature of the jacket.
[src:chemical-energy/calorimeter] Heat is measured by monitoring the temperature difference between heat transfer fluid and the process fluid.
[src:chemical-energy/calorimeter] In addition, fill volumes (i.e. wetted area), specific heat, heat transfer coefficient have to be determined to arrive at a correct value.
[src:chemical-energy/calorimeter] It is possible with this type of calorimeter to do reactions at reflux, although it is very less accurate.
[src:chemical-energy/calorimeter] The cooling/heating jacket controls the temperature of the process.
[src:chemical-energy/calorimeter] Heat is measured by monitoring the heat gained or lost by the heat transfer fluid.
[src:chemical-energy/calorimeter] Power compensation uses a heater placed within the vessel to maintain a constant temperature.
[src:chemical-energy/calorimeter] The energy supplied to this heater can be varied as reactions require and the calorimetry signal is purely derived from this electrical power.
[src:chemical-energy/calorimeter] Constant flux calorimetry (or COFLUX as it is often termed) is derived from heat balance calorimetry and uses specialized control mechanisms to maintain a constant heat flow (or flux) across the vessel wall.
[src:chemical-energy/calorimeter] A bomb calorimeter is a type of constant-volume calorimeter used in measuring the heat of combustion of a particular reaction.
[src:chemical-energy/calorimeter] Bomb calorimeters have to withstand the large pressure within the calorimeter as the reaction is being measured.
[src:chemical-energy/calorimeter] Electrical energy is used to ignite the fuel; as the fuel is burning, it will heat up the surrounding air, which expands and escapes through a tube that leads the air out of the calorimeter.
[src:chemical-energy/calorimeter] When the air is escaping through the copper tube it will also heat up the water outside the tube.
[src:chemical-energy/calorimeter] The change in temperature of the water allows for calculating calorie content of the fuel.
[src:chemical-energy/calorimeter] 2000 ml) before the charge is electrically ignited.
[src:chemical-energy/calorimeter] The bomb, with the known mass of the sample and oxygen, form a closed system — no gases escape during the reaction.
[src:chemical-energy/calorimeter] The weighed reactant put inside the steel container is then ignited.
[src:chemical-energy/calorimeter] Energy is released by the combustion and heat flow from this crosses the stainless steel wall, thus raising the temperature of the steel bomb, its contents, and the surrounding water jacket.
[src:chemical-energy/calorimeter] The temperature change in the water is then accurately measured with a thermometer.
[src:chemical-energy/calorimeter] This reading, along with a bomb factor (which is dependent on the heat capacity of the metal bomb parts), is used to calculate the energy given out by the sample burn.
[src:chemical-energy/calorimeter] A small correction is made to account for the electrical energy input, the burning fuse, and acid production (by titration of the residual liquid).
[src:chemical-energy/calorimeter] After the temperature rise has been measured, the excess pressure in the bomb is released.
[src:chemical-energy/calorimeter] At its core, a bomb calorimeter consists of a small cup to contain the sample, oxygen, a stainless steel bomb, water, a stirrer, a thermometer, the dewar or insulating container (to prevent heat flow from the calorimeter to its surroundings) and an ignition circuit connected to the bomb.
[src:chemical-energy/calorimeter] By using stainless steel for the bomb, the reaction will occur with no volume change observed.
[src:chemical-energy/calorimeter] Before the bomb can be used to determine heat of combustion of any compound, it must be calibrated.
[src:chemical-energy/calorimeter] A small factor contributes to the correction of the total heat of combustion is the fuse wire.
[src:chemical-energy/calorimeter] Nickel fuse wire is often used and has heat of combustion: 981.2 cal/g.
[src:chemical-energy/calorimeter] In order to calibrate the bomb, a small amount (~ 1 g) of benzoic acid, or p-methyl benzoic acid is weighed.
[src:chemical-energy/calorimeter] A length of nickel fuse wire (~10 cm) is weighed both before and after the combustion process.
[src:chemical-energy/calorimeter] The higher pressure and concentration of O 2 in the bomb system can render combustible some compounds that are not normally flammable.
[src:chemical-energy/calorimeter] Some substances do not combust completely, making the calculations harder as the remaining mass has to be taken into consideration, making the possible error considerably larger and compromising the data.
[src:chemical-energy/calorimeter] When working with compounds that are not as flammable (that might not combust completely) one solution would be to mix the compound with some flammable compounds with a known heat of combustion and make a pallet with the mixture.
[src:chemical-energy/calorimeter] The detection is based on a three-dimensional fluxmeter sensor.
[src:chemical-energy/calorimeter] The fluxmeter element consists of a ring of several thermocouples in series.
[src:chemical-energy/calorimeter] The corresponding thermopile of high thermal conductivity surrounds the experimental space within the calorimetric block.
[src:chemical-energy/calorimeter] The radial arrangement of the thermopiles guarantees an almost complete integration of the heat.
[src:chemical-energy/calorimeter] This is verified by the calculation of the efficiency ratio that indicates that an average value of 94% ± 1% of heat is transmitted through the sensor on the full range of temperature of the Calvet-type calorimeter.
[src:chemical-energy/calorimeter] In this setup, the sensitivity of the calorimeter is not affected by the crucible, the type of purgegas, or the flow rate.
[src:chemical-energy/calorimeter] The main advantage of the setup is the increase of the experimental vessel's size and consequently the size of the sample, without affecting the accuracy of the calorimetric measurement.
[src:chemical-energy/calorimeter] The calibration of the calorimetric detectors is a key parameter and has to be performed very carefully.
[src:chemical-energy/calorimeter] For Calvet-type calorimeters, a specific calibration, so called Joule effect or electrical calibration, has been developed to overcome all the problems encountered by a calibration done with standard materials.
[src:chemical-energy/calorimeter] An example of Calvet-type calorimeter is the C80 Calorimeter (reaction, isothermal and scanning calorimeter).
[src:chemical-energy/calorimeter] Sometimes referred to as **constant-pressure calorimeters**, adiabatic calorimeters measure the change in enthalpy of a reaction occurring in solution during which the no heat exchange with the surroundings is allowed (adiabatic) and the atmospheric pressure remains constant.
[src:chemical-energy/calorimeter] An example is a coffee-cup calorimeter, which is constructed from two nested Styrofoam cups, providing insulation from the surroundings, and a lid with two holes, allowing insertion of a thermometer and a stirring rod.
[src:chemical-energy/calorimeter] The inner cup holds a known amount of a solvent, usually water, that absorbs the heat from the reaction.
[src:chemical-energy/calorimeter] When the reaction occurs, the outer cup provides insulation.
[src:chemical-energy/calorimeter] The measurement of heat using a simple calorimeter, like the coffee cup calorimeter, is an example of constant-pressure calorimetry, since the pressure (atmospheric pressure) remains constant during the process.
[src:chemical-energy/calorimeter] Constant-pressure calorimetry is used in determining the changes in enthalpy occurring in solution.
[src:chemical-energy/calorimeter] Under these conditions the change in enthalpy equals the heat.
[src:chemical-energy/calorimeter] Commercial calorimeters operate in a similar way.
[src:chemical-energy/calorimeter] The semi-adiabatic (isoperibol) calorimeters measure temperature changes up to 10−6 °C and account for heat loss through the walls of the reaction vessel to the environment, hence, semi-adiabatic.
[src:chemical-energy/calorimeter] The reaction vessel is a dewar flask which is immersed in a constant temperature bath.
[src:chemical-energy/calorimeter] This provides a constant heat leak rate that can be corrected through the software.
[src:chemical-energy/calorimeter] The heat capacity of the reactants (and the vessel) are measured by introducing a known amount of heat using a heater element (voltage and current) and measuring the temperature change.
[src:chemical-energy/calorimeter] Adiabatic calorimeters most commonly used in materials science research to study reactions that occur at a constant pressure and volume.
[src:chemical-energy/calorimeter] They are particularly useful for determining the heat capacity of substances, measuring the enthalpy changes of chemical reactions, and studying the thermodynamic properties of materials.
[src:chemical-energy/calorimeter] In a **differential scanning calorimeter** (DSC), heat flow into a sample—usually contained in a small aluminium capsule or 'pan'—is measured differentially, i.e., by comparing it to the flow into an empty reference pan.
[src:chemical-energy/calorimeter] In a **heat flux DSC**, both pans sit on a small slab of material with a known (calibrated) heat resistance K.
[src:chemical-energy/calorimeter] This time linearity requires good design and good (computerized) temperature control.
[src:chemical-energy/calorimeter] Of course, controlled cooling and isothermal experiments are also possible.
[src:chemical-energy/calorimeter] Heat flows into the two pans by conduction.
[src:chemical-energy/calorimeter] The flow of heat into the sample is larger because of its heat capacity *C*p.
[src:chemical-energy/calorimeter] The difference in flow *dq*/*dt* induces a small temperature difference Δ*T* across the slab.
[src:chemical-energy/calorimeter] This temperature difference is measured using a thermocouple.
[src:chemical-energy/calorimeter] When suddenly heat is absorbed by the sample (e.g., when the sample melts), the signal will respond and exhibit a peak.
[src:chemical-energy/calorimeter] From the integral of this peak the enthalpy of melting can be determined, and from its onset the melting temperature.
[src:chemical-energy/calorimeter] Differential scanning calorimetry is a workhorse technique in many fields, particularly in polymer characterization.
[src:chemical-energy/calorimeter] A **modulated temperature differential scanning calorimeter** (MTDSC) is a type of DSC in which a small oscillation is imposed upon the otherwise linear heating rate.
[src:chemical-energy/calorimeter] It facilitates the direct measurement of the heat capacity in one measurement, even in (quasi-)isothermal conditions.
[src:chemical-energy/calorimeter] It permits the simultaneous measurement of heat effects that respond to a changing heating rate (reversing) and that don't respond to the changing heating rate (non-reversing).
[src:chemical-energy/calorimeter] It allows for the optimization of both sensitivity and resolution in a single test by allowing for a slow average heating rate (optimizing resolution) and a fast changing heating rate (optimizing sensitivity).
[src:chemical-energy/calorimeter] A DSC may also be used as an initial safety screening tool.
[src:chemical-energy/calorimeter] In this mode the sample will be housed in a non-reactive crucible (often gold, or gold-plated steel), and which will be able to withstand pressure (typically up to 100 bar).
[src:chemical-energy/calorimeter] The presence of an exothermic event can then be used to assess the stability of a substance to heat.
[src:chemical-energy/calorimeter] A much more accurate data set can be obtained from an adiabatic calorimeter, but such a test may take 2–3 days from ambient at a rate of 3 °C increment per half hour.
[src:chemical-energy/calorimeter] In an isothermal titration calorimeter, the heat of reaction is used to follow a titration experiment.
[src:chemical-energy/calorimeter] The technique is gaining in importance particularly in the field of biochemistry, because it facilitates determination of substrate binding to enzymes.
[src:chemical-energy/calorimeter] The technique is commonly used in the pharmaceutical industry to characterize potential drug candidates.
[src:chemical-energy/calorimeter] The Continuous Reaction Calorimeter is especially suitable to obtain thermodynamic information for a scale-up of continuous processes in tubular reactors.
[src:chemical-energy/calorimeter] This is useful because the released heat can strongly depend on the reaction control, especially for non-selective reactions.
[src:chemical-energy/calorimeter] With the Continuous Reaction Calorimeter an axial temperature profile along the tube reactor can be recorded and the specific heat of reaction can be determined by means of heat balances and segmental dynamic parameters.
[src:chemical-energy/calorimeter] The system must consist of a tubular reactor, dosing systems, preheaters, temperature sensors and flow meters.
[src:chemical-energy/calorimeter] In traditional heat flow calorimeters, one reactant is added continuously in small amounts, similar to a semi-batch process, in order to obtain a complete conversion of the reaction.
[src:chemical-energy/calorimeter] In contrast to the tubular reactor, this leads to longer residence times, different substance concentrations and flatter temperature profiles.
[src:chemical-energy/calorimeter] Thus, the selectivity of not well-defined reactions can be affected.
[src:chemical-energy/calorimeter] This can lead to the formation of by-products or consecutive products which alter the measured heat of reaction, since other bonds are formed.
[src:chemical-energy/calorimeter] The amount of by-product or secondary product can be found by calculating the yield of the desired product.
[src:chemical-energy/calorimeter] If the heat of reaction measured in the HFC (Heat flow calorimetry) and PFR calorimeter differ, most probably some side reactions have occurred.
[src:chemical-energy/calorimeter] They could for example be caused by different temperatures and residence times.
[src:chemical-energy/calorimeter] The totally measured Qr is composed of partially overlapped reaction enthalpies (ΔHr) of main and side reactions, depending on their degrees of conversion (U).
[src:chemical-energy/calorimeter] Calorimeters can be used to measure the efficiency of geothermal energy conversion processes.
[src:chemical-energy/calorimeter] Through measuring the heat input and output of the process, engineers can determine how effective the plant is at converting geothermal energy into usable electricity or other forms of energy.
[src:chemical-energy/calorimeter] Calorimeters can also monitor the quality of the steam extracted from the geothermal resource.
[src:chemical-energy/calorimeter] By analyzing the heat content of the steam, engineers can ensure that the resource meets the required specifications for efficient energy production.
[src:chemical-energy/capacitor-p01] A **capacitor** is a device that stores electrical energy by accumulating electric charges on two closely spaced surfaces that are insulated from each other.
[src:chemical-energy/capacitor-p01] It is a passive electronic component with two terminals.
[src:chemical-energy/capacitor-p01] A capacitor was originally known as a **condenser**, a term still encountered in a few compound names, such as the *condenser microphone*.
[src:chemical-energy/capacitor-p01] Colloquially, a capacitor may be called a ***cap***.
[src:chemical-energy/capacitor-p01] The utility of a capacitor depends on its capacitance.
[src:chemical-energy/capacitor-p01] While some capacitance exists between any two electrical conductors in proximity in a circuit, a capacitor is a component designed specifically to add capacitance to some part of the circuit.
[src:chemical-energy/capacitor-p01] The physical form and construction of practical capacitors vary widely and many types of capacitor are in common use.
[src:chemical-energy/capacitor-p01] Most capacitors contain at least two electrical conductors, often in the form of metallic plates or surfaces separated by a dielectric medium.
[src:chemical-energy/capacitor-p01] A conductor may be a foil, thin film, sintered bead of metal, or an electrolyte.
[src:chemical-energy/capacitor-p01] The nonconducting dielectric acts to increase the capacitor's charge capacity.
[src:chemical-energy/capacitor-p01] Materials commonly used as dielectrics include glass, ceramic, plastic film, paper, mica, air, and oxide layers.
[src:chemical-energy/capacitor-p01] No current actually flows through a perfect dielectric.
[src:chemical-energy/capacitor-p01] However, there is a flow of charge through the source circuit.
[src:chemical-energy/capacitor-p01] If the condition is maintained sufficiently long, the current through the source circuit ceases.
[src:chemical-energy/capacitor-p01] If a time-varying voltage is applied across the leads of the capacitor, the source experiences an ongoing current due to the charging and discharging cycles of the capacitor.
[src:chemical-energy/capacitor-p01] Capacitors are widely used as parts of electrical circuits in many common electrical devices.
[src:chemical-energy/capacitor-p01] Unlike a resistor, an ideal capacitor does not dissipate energy, although real-life capacitors do dissipate a small amount .
[src:chemical-energy/capacitor-p01] The earliest forms of capacitors were created in the 1740s, when European experimenters discovered that electric charge could be stored in water-filled glass jars that came to be known as Leyden jars.
[src:chemical-energy/capacitor-p01] Today, capacitors are widely used in electronic circuits for blocking direct current while allowing alternating current to pass.
[src:chemical-energy/capacitor-p01] In analog filter networks, they smooth the output of power supplies.
[src:chemical-energy/capacitor-p01] In resonant circuits they tune radios to particular frequencies.
[src:chemical-energy/capacitor-p01] In electric power transmission systems, they stabilize voltage and power flow.
[src:chemical-energy/capacitor-p01] The property of energy storage in capacitors was exploited as dynamic memory in early digital computers, and still is in modern DRAM.
[src:chemical-energy/capacitor-p01] The most common example of natural capacitance are the static charges accumulated between clouds in the sky and the surface of the Earth, where the air between them serves as the dielectric.
[src:chemical-energy/capacitor-p01] This results in bolts of lightning when the breakdown voltage of the air is exceeded.
[src:chemical-energy/capacitor-p01] In October 1745, Ewald Georg von Kleist of Pomerania, Germany, found that charge could be stored by connecting a high-voltage electrostatic generator by a wire to a volume of water in a hand-held glass jar.
[src:chemical-energy/capacitor-p01] Von Kleist's hand and the water acted as conductors and the jar as a dielectric (although details of the mechanism were incorrectly identified at the time).
[src:chemical-energy/capacitor-p01] Von Kleist found that touching the wire resulted in a powerful spark, much more painful than that obtained from an electrostatic machine.
[src:chemical-energy/capacitor-p01] The following year, the Dutch physicist Pieter van Musschenbroek invented a similar capacitor, which was named the Leyden jar, after the University of Leiden where he worked.
[src:chemical-energy/capacitor-p01] Daniel Gralath was the first to combine several jars in parallel to increase the charge storage capacity.
[src:chemical-energy/capacitor-p01] Benjamin Franklin investigated the Leyden jar and came to the conclusion that the charge was stored on the glass, not in the water as others had assumed.
[src:chemical-energy/capacitor-p01] He also adopted the term "battery", (denoting the increase of power with a row of similar units as in a battery of cannon), subsequently applied to clusters of electrochemical cells.
[src:chemical-energy/capacitor-p01] In 1747, Leyden jars were made by coating the inside and outside of jars with metal foil, leaving a space at the mouth to prevent arcing between the foils.
[src:chemical-energy/capacitor-p01] The earliest unit of capacitance was the jar, equivalent to about 1.11 nanofarads.
[src:chemical-energy/capacitor-p01] More compact construction methods began to be used, such as a flexible dielectric sheet (like oiled paper) sandwiched between sheets of metal foil, rolled or folded into a small package.
[src:chemical-energy/capacitor-p01] Early capacitors were known as *condensers*, a term that is still occasionally used today, particularly in high power applications, such as automotive systems.
[src:chemical-energy/capacitor-p01] The term became deprecated because of the ambiguous meaning of steam condenser, with *capacitor* being recommended by the British Engineering Standards Association in 1926, although it took several decades for the term to predominate.
[src:chemical-energy/capacitor-p01] Since the beginning of the study of electricity, non-conductive materials like glass, porcelain, paper and mica have been used as insulators.
[src:chemical-energy/capacitor-p01] Decades later, these materials were also well-suited for use as the dielectric for the first capacitors.
[src:chemical-energy/capacitor-p01] Paper capacitors, made by sandwiching a strip of impregnated paper between strips of metal and rolling the result into a cylinder, were commonly used in the late 19th century; their manufacture started in 1876, and they were used from the early 20th century as decoupling capacitors in telephony.
[src:chemical-energy/capacitor-p01] Porcelain was used in the first ceramic capacitors.
[src:chemical-energy/capacitor-p01] In the early years of Marconi's wireless transmitting apparatus, porcelain capacitors were used for high voltage and high frequency application in the transmitters.
[src:chemical-energy/capacitor-p01] On the receiver side, smaller mica capacitors were used for resonant circuits.
[src:chemical-energy/capacitor-p01] Mica capacitors were invented in 1909 by William Dubilier.
[src:chemical-energy/capacitor-p01] Prior to World War II, mica was the most common dielectric for capacitors in the United States.
[src:chemical-energy/capacitor-p01] Charles Pollak (born Karol Pollak), the inventor of the first electrolytic capacitors, found out that the oxide layer on an aluminum anode remained stable in a neutral or alkaline electrolyte, even when the power was switched off.
[src:chemical-energy/capacitor-p01] 672,913 for an "Electric liquid capacitor with aluminum electrodes".
[src:chemical-energy/capacitor-p01] Solid electrolyte tantalum capacitors were invented by Bell Laboratories in the early 1950s as a miniaturized and more reliable low-voltage support capacitor to complement their newly invented transistor.
[src:chemical-energy/capacitor-p01] With the development of plastic materials by organic chemists during the Second World War, the capacitor industry began to replace paper with thinner polymer films.
[src:chemical-energy/capacitor-p01] One very early development in film capacitors was described in British Patent 587,953 in 1944.
[src:chemical-energy/capacitor-p01] Electric double-layer capacitors (now supercapacitors) were invented in 1957 when H.
[src:chemical-energy/capacitor-p01] Becker developed a "Low voltage electrolytic capacitor with porous carbon electrodes".
[src:chemical-energy/capacitor-p01] He believed that the energy was stored as a charge in the carbon pores used in his capacitor as in the pores of the etched foils of electrolytic capacitors.
[src:chemical-energy/capacitor-p01] The MOS capacitor was later widely adopted as a storage capacitor in memory chips, and as the basic building block of the charge-coupled device (CCD) in image sensor technology.
[src:chemical-energy/capacitor-p01] Robert Dennard invented modern DRAM architecture, combining a single MOS transistor per capacitor.
[src:chemical-energy/capacitor-p01] A capacitor consists of two conductors separated by a non-conductive region.
[src:chemical-energy/capacitor-p01] The non-conductive region can either be a vacuum or an electrical insulator material known as a dielectric.
[src:chemical-energy/capacitor-p01] Examples of dielectric media are glass, air, paper, plastic, ceramic, and even a semiconductor depletion region chemically identical to the conductors.
[src:chemical-energy/capacitor-p01] From Coulomb's law, a charge on one conductor will exert a force on the charge carriers within the other conductor, attracting opposite polarity charge and repelling like polarity charges, thus an opposite polarity charge will be induced on the surface of the other conductor.
[src:chemical-energy/capacitor-p01] The conductors thus hold equal and opposite charges on their facing surfaces, and the dielectric develops an electric field.
[src:chemical-energy/capacitor-p01] A capacitance of one farad (1 F) means that one coulomb of charge on each conductor causes a voltage of one volt across the device.
[src:chemical-energy/capacitor-p01] Because the conductors (or plates) are close together, the opposite charges on the conductors attract one another due to their electric fields, allowing the capacitor to store more charge for a given voltage than when the conductors are separated, yielding a larger capacitance.
[src:chemical-energy/capacitor-p01] In practical devices, charge build-up sometimes affects the capacitor mechanically, causing its capacitance to vary.
[src:chemical-energy/capacitor-p01] In the hydraulic analogy, voltage is analogous to water pressure and electrical current through a wire is analogous to water flow through a pipe.
[src:chemical-energy/capacitor-p01] A capacitor is like an elastic diaphragm within the pipe.
[src:chemical-energy/capacitor-p01] Although water cannot pass through the diaphragm, it moves as the diaphragm stretches or un-stretches.
[src:chemical-energy/capacitor-p01] In a circuit, a capacitor can behave differently at different time instants.
[src:chemical-energy/capacitor-p01] The simplest model of a capacitor consists of two thin parallel conductive plates each with an area of A separated by a uniform gap of thickness d filled with a dielectric of permittivity ⁠ $\varepsilon$ ⁠.
[src:chemical-energy/capacitor-p01] It is assumed the gap d is much smaller than the dimensions of the plates.
[src:chemical-energy/capacitor-p01] This model applies well to many practical capacitors which are constructed of metal sheets separated by a thin layer of insulating dielectric, since manufacturers try to keep the dielectric very uniform in thickness to avoid thin spots which can cause failure of the capacitor.
[src:chemical-energy/capacitor-p01] This "fringing field" area is approximately the same width as the plate separation, ⁠ d ⁠, and assuming d is small compared to the plate dimensions, it is small enough to be ignored.
[src:chemical-energy/capacitor-p01] From Gauss's law the magnitude of the electric field between the plates is ⁠ $\textstyle E={\sigma \over \varepsilon }$ ⁠.
[src:chemical-energy/capacitor-p01] Therefore, in a capacitor the highest capacitance is achieved with a high permittivity dielectric material, large plate area, and small separation between the plates.
[src:chemical-energy/capacitor-p01] Since the area A of the plates increases with the square of the linear dimensions and the separation d increases linearly, the capacitance scales with the linear dimension of a capacitor (⁠ $C\varpropto L$ ⁠), or as the cube root of the volume.
[src:chemical-energy/capacitor-p01] A parallel plate capacitor can only store a finite amount of energy before dielectric breakdown occurs.
[src:chemical-energy/capacitor-p01] The capacitor's dielectric material has a dielectric strength *U*d which sets the capacitor's breakdown voltage at *V* = *V*bd = *U*d*d*.
[src:chemical-energy/capacitor-p01] The maximum energy is a function of dielectric volume, permittivity, and dielectric strength.
[src:chemical-energy/capacitor-p01] Changing the plate area and the separation between the plates while maintaining the same volume causes no change of the maximum amount of energy that the capacitor can store, so long as the distance between plates remains much smaller than both the length and width of the plates.
[src:chemical-energy/capacitor-p01] In addition, these equations assume that the electric field is entirely concentrated in the dielectric between the plates.
[src:chemical-energy/capacitor-p01] In reality there are fringing fields outside the dielectric, for example between the sides of the capacitor plates, which increase the effective capacitance of the capacitor.
[src:chemical-energy/capacitor-p01] This is sometimes called parasitic capacitance.
[src:chemical-energy/capacitor-p01] For some simple capacitor geometries this additional capacitance term can be calculated analytically.
[src:chemical-energy/capacitor-p01] It becomes negligibly small when the ratios of plate width to separation and length to separation are large.
[src:chemical-energy/capacitor-p01] For n number of plates in a capacitor, the total capacitance would be $C=\varepsilon _{o}{\frac {A}{d}}(n-1)$ where ${\textstyle C={\frac {\varepsilon _{o}A}{d}}}$ is the capacitance for a single plate and n is the number of interleaved plates.
[src:chemical-energy/capacitor-p01] As shown to the figure on the right, the interleaved plates can be seen as parallel plates connected to each other.
[src:chemical-energy/capacitor-p01] Every pair of adjacent plates acts as a separate capacitor; the number of pairs is always one less than the number of plates, hence the $(n-1)$ multiplier.
[src:chemical-energy/capacitor-p01] To increase the charge and voltage on a capacitor, work must be done by an external power source to move charge from the negative to the positive plate against the opposing force of the electric field.
[src:chemical-energy/capacitor-p01] If the voltage on the capacitor is ⁠ V ⁠, the work $\mathrm {d} W$ required to move a small increment of charge $\mathrm {d} q$ from the negative to the positive plate is ⁠ $\mathrm {d} W=V\mathop {} \!\mathrm {d} q$ ⁠.
[src:chemical-energy/capacitor-p01] The energy is stored in the increased electric field between the plates.
[src:chemical-energy/capacitor-p01] This potential energy will remain in the capacitor until the charge is removed.
[src:chemical-energy/capacitor-p01] If charge is allowed to move back from the positive to the negative plate, for example by connecting a circuit with resistance between the plates, the charge moving under the influence of the electric field will do work on the external circuit.
[src:chemical-energy/capacitor-p01] If the gap between the capacitor plates d is constant, as in the parallel plate model above, the electric field between the plates will be uniform (neglecting fringing fields) and will have a constant value ⁠ $E=V/d$ ⁠.
[src:chemical-energy/capacitor-p01] The current $I(t)$ through any component in an electric circuit is defined as the rate of flow of a charge $Q(t)$ passing through it.
[src:chemical-energy/capacitor-p01] Actual charges – electrons – cannot pass through the dielectric of an *ideal* capacitor.
[src:chemical-energy/capacitor-p01] Rather, one electron accumulates on the negative plate for each one that leaves the positive plate, resulting in an electron depletion and consequent positive charge on one electrode that is equal and opposite to the accumulated negative charge on the other.
[src:chemical-energy/capacitor-p01] Thus the charge on the electrodes is equal to the integral of the current as well as proportional to the voltage, as discussed above.
[src:chemical-energy/capacitor-p01] As with any antiderivative, a constant of integration is added to represent the initial voltage ⁠ $V(t_{0})$ ⁠).
[src:chemical-energy/capacitor-p01] for C independent of time, voltage and electric charge.
[src:chemical-energy/capacitor-p01] The dual of the capacitor is the inductor, which stores energy in a magnetic field rather than an electric field.
[src:chemical-energy/capacitor-p01] Its current-voltage relation is obtained by exchanging current and voltage in the capacitor equations and replacing C with the inductance L.
[src:chemical-energy/capacitor-p01] A series circuit containing only a resistor, a capacitor, a switch and a constant DC source of voltage *V*0 is known as a *charging circuit*.
[src:chemical-energy/capacitor-p01] At *t* = 0, the voltage across the capacitor is zero and the voltage across the resistor is *V*0.
[src:chemical-energy/capacitor-p01] The initial current is then ⁠ $\textstyle I(0)={V_{0} \over R}$ ⁠.
[src:chemical-energy/capacitor-p01] As the capacitor reaches equilibrium with the source voltage, the voltages across the resistor and the current through the entire circuit decay exponentially.
[src:chemical-energy/capacitor-p01] In the case of a *discharging* capacitor, the capacitor's initial voltage (*V*Ci) replaces *V*0.
[src:chemical-energy/capacitor-p01] Impedance, the vector sum of reactance and resistance, describes the phase difference and the ratio of amplitudes between sinusoidally varying voltage and sinusoidally varying current at a given frequency.
[src:chemical-energy/capacitor-p01] Fourier analysis allows any signal to be constructed from a spectrum of frequencies, whence the circuit's reaction to the various frequencies may be found.
[src:chemical-energy/capacitor-p01] The ⁠ $-j$ ⁠ phase indicates that the AC voltage ⁠ $V=ZI$ ⁠ lags the AC current by 90°: the positive current phase corresponds to increasing voltage as the capacitor charges; zero current corresponds to instantaneous constant voltage.
[src:chemical-energy/capacitor-p01] Impedance decreases with increasing capacitance and increasing frequency.
[src:chemical-energy/capacitor-p01] This implies that a higher-frequency signal or a larger capacitor results in a lower voltage amplitude per current amplitude – an AC "short circuit" or AC coupling.
[src:chemical-energy/capacitor-p01] Conversely, for very low frequencies, the reactance is high, so that a capacitor is nearly an open circuit in AC analysis – those frequencies have been "filtered out".
[src:chemical-energy/capacitor-p01] Capacitors are different from resistors and inductors in that the impedance is *inversely* proportional to the defining characteristic; i.e., capacitance.
[src:chemical-energy/capacitor-p01] A capacitor connected to an alternating voltage source has a displacement current to flowing through it.
[src:chemical-energy/capacitor-p01] At ⁠ $\sin(\omega t)=-1$ ⁠, the capacitor has a maximum (or peak) current whereby ⁠ $I_{0}=\omega CV_{0}$ ⁠.
[src:chemical-energy/capacitor-p01] In this situation, the current is out of phase with the voltage by ⁠ $\textstyle +{\pi \over 2}$ ⁠ radians or +90 degrees, i.e. the current leads the voltage by 90°.
[src:chemical-energy/capacitor-p01] Capacitors in a parallel configuration each have the same applied voltage.
[src:chemical-energy/capacitor-p01] Charge is apportioned among them by capacitance value.
[src:chemical-energy/capacitor-p01] Connected in series, the schematic diagram reveals that the separation distance, not the plate area, adds up.
[src:chemical-energy/capacitor-p01] The capacitors each store instantaneous charge build-up equal to that of every other capacitor in the series.
[src:chemical-energy/capacitor-p01] The total voltage difference from end to end is apportioned to each capacitor according to the inverse of its capacitance.
[src:chemical-energy/capacitor-p01] Capacitors are combined in series to achieve a higher working voltage, for example for smoothing a high voltage power supply.
[src:chemical-energy/capacitor-p01] The voltage ratings, which are based on plate separation, add up, if capacitance and leakage currents for each capacitor are identical.
[src:chemical-energy/capacitor-p01] In such an application, on occasion, series strings are connected in parallel, forming a matrix.
[src:chemical-energy/capacitor-p01] The goal is to maximize the energy storage of the network without overloading any capacitor.
[src:chemical-energy/capacitor-p01] For high-energy storage with capacitors in series, some safety considerations must be applied to ensure one capacitor failing and leaking current does not apply too much voltage to the other series capacitors.
[src:chemical-energy/capacitor-p01] Series connection is also sometimes used to adapt polarized electrolytic capacitors for bipolar AC use.
[src:chemical-energy/capacitor-p01] (Note that this is only correct if all capacitance values are equal).
[src:chemical-energy/capacitor-p01] In practice, capacitors deviate from the ideal capacitor equation in several aspects.
[src:chemical-energy/capacitor-p01] Some of these, such as leakage current and parasitic effects are linear, or can be analyzed as nearly linear, and can be accounted for by adding virtual components to form an equivalent circuit.
[src:chemical-energy/capacitor-p01] The usual methods of network analysis can then be applied.
[src:chemical-energy/capacitor-p01] In other cases, such as with breakdown voltage, the effect is non-linear and ordinary (normal, e.g., linear) network analysis cannot be used, the effect must be considered separately.
[src:chemical-energy/capacitor-p01] Yet another group of artifacts may exist, including temperature dependence, that may be linear but invalidates the assumption in the analysis that capacitance is a constant.
[src:chemical-energy/capacitor-p01] Finally, combined parasitic effects such as inherent inductance, resistance, or dielectric losses can exhibit non-uniform behavior at varying frequencies of operation.
[src:chemical-energy/capacitor-p01] Above a particular electric field strength, known as the dielectric strength ⁠ $E_{\mathrm {ds} }$ ⁠, the dielectric in a capacitor becomes conductive.
[src:chemical-energy/capacitor-p01] The maximum energy that can be stored safely in a capacitor is limited by the breakdown voltage.
[src:chemical-energy/capacitor-p01] Exceeding this voltage can result in a short circuit between the plates, which can often cause permanent damage to the dielectric, plates, or both.
[src:chemical-energy/capacitor-p01] Due to the scaling of capacitance and breakdown voltage with dielectric thickness, all capacitors made with a particular dielectric have approximately equal maximum energy density, to the extent that the dielectric dominates their volume.
[src:chemical-energy/capacitor-p01] For air dielectric capacitors the breakdown field strength is of the order 2–5 MV/m (or equivalently in kilovolts per millimeter); for mica the breakdown is 100–300 MV/m; for oil, 15–25 MV/m; it can be much less when other materials are used for the dielectric.
[src:chemical-energy/capacitor-p01] The dielectric is used in very thin layers and so absolute breakdown voltage of capacitors is limited.
[src:chemical-energy/capacitor-p01] Typical ratings for capacitors used for general electronics applications range from a few volts to 1 kilovolt.
[src:chemical-energy/capacitor-p01] As the voltage increases, the dielectric must be thicker, making high-voltage capacitors larger per capacitance than those rated for lower voltages.
[src:chemical-energy/capacitor-p01] The breakdown voltage is critically affected by factors such as the geometry of the capacitor conductive parts; sharp edges or points increase the electric field strength at that point and can lead to a local breakdown.
[src:chemical-energy/capacitor-p01] Once this starts to happen, the breakdown quickly tracks through the dielectric until it reaches the opposite plate, leaving carbon behind and causing a short (or relatively low resistance) circuit.
[src:chemical-energy/capacitor-p01] The results can be explosive, as the short in the capacitor draws current from the surrounding circuitry and dissipates the energy.
[src:chemical-energy/capacitor-p01] However, in capacitors with particular dielectrics and thin metal electrodes, shorts are not formed after breakdown.
[src:chemical-energy/capacitor-p01] It happens because a metal melts or evaporates in a breakdown vicinity, isolating it from the rest of the capacitor.
[src:chemical-energy/capacitor-p01] The usual breakdown route is that the field strength becomes large enough to pull electrons in the dielectric from their atoms thus causing conduction.
[src:chemical-energy/capacitor-p01] Other scenarios are possible, such as impurities in the dielectric, and, if the dielectric is of a crystalline nature, imperfections in the crystal structure can result in an avalanche breakdown as seen in semi-conductor devices.
[src:chemical-energy/capacitor-p01] Breakdown voltage is also affected by pressure, humidity and temperature.
[src:chemical-energy/capacitor-p01] An ideal capacitor only stores and releases electrical energy, without dissipation.
[src:chemical-energy/capacitor-p01] As frequency increases, the capacitive impedance (a negative reactance) reduces, so the dielectric's conductance becomes less important and the series components become more significant.
[src:chemical-energy/capacitor-p01] Thus, a simplified RLC series model valid for a large frequency range simply treats the capacitor as being in series with an equivalent series inductance ${\text{ESL}}$ and a frequency-dependent *equivalent series resistance* ${\text{ESR}}$ , which varies little with frequency.
[src:chemical-energy/capacitor-p01] Unlike the previous model, this model is not valid at DC and very low frequencies where $G_{\text{dielectric}}$ is relevant.
[src:chemical-energy/capacitor-p01] Inductive reactance increases with frequency.
[src:chemical-energy/capacitor-p01] Because its sign is positive, it counteracts the capacitance.
[src:chemical-energy/capacitor-p01] At the RLC circuit's natural frequency $\omega _{0}{=}{\tfrac {1}{\sqrt {{\text{ESL}}\cdot {\text{C}}}}}$ , the inductance perfectly cancels the capacitance, so total reactance is zero.
[src:chemical-energy/capacitor-p01] Since the total impedance at $\omega _{0}$ is just the real-value of ${\text{ESR}}$ , average power dissipation reaches its maximum of ⁠VRMS2/ESR⁠, where VRMS is the root mean square (RMS) voltage across the capacitor.
[src:chemical-energy/capacitor-p01] At even higher frequencies, the inductive impedance dominates, so the capacitor undesirably behaves instead like an inductor.
[src:chemical-energy/capacitor-p01] High-frequency engineering involves accounting for the inductance of all connections and components.
[src:chemical-energy/capacitor-p01] The ⁠ Q ⁠ factor is a measure of its efficiency: the higher the ⁠ Q ⁠ factor of the capacitor, the closer it approaches the behavior of an ideal capacitor.
[src:chemical-energy/capacitor-p01] Ripple current is the AC component of an applied source (often a switched-mode power supply) whose frequency may be constant or varying.
[src:chemical-energy/capacitor-p01] Ripple current causes heat to be generated within the capacitor due to the dielectric losses caused by the changing field strength together with the current flow across the slightly resistive supply lines or the electrolyte in the capacitor.
[src:chemical-energy/capacitor-p01] The equivalent series resistance (ESR) is the amount of internal series resistance one would add to a perfect capacitor to model this.
[src:chemical-energy/capacitor-p01] Some types of capacitors, primarily tantalum and aluminum electrolytic capacitors, as well as some film capacitors have a specified rating value for maximum ripple current.
[src:chemical-energy/capacitor-p01] The capacitance of certain capacitors decreases as the component ages.
[src:chemical-energy/capacitor-p01] In ceramic capacitors, this is caused by degradation of the dielectric.
[src:chemical-energy/capacitor-p01] The type of dielectric, ambient operating and storage temperatures are the most significant aging factors, while the operating voltage usually has a smaller effect, i.e., usual capacitor design is to minimize voltage coefficient.
[src:chemical-energy/capacitor-p01] The aging process may be reversed by heating the component above the Curie point.
[src:chemical-energy/capacitor-p01] Aging is fastest near the beginning of life of the component, and the device stabilizes over time.
[src:chemical-energy/capacitor-p01] Electrolytic capacitors age as the electrolyte evaporates.
[src:chemical-energy/capacitor-p01] In contrast with ceramic capacitors, this occurs towards the end of life of the component.
[src:chemical-energy/capacitor-p01] Temperature dependence of capacitance is usually expressed in parts per million (ppm) per °C.
[src:chemical-energy/capacitor-p01] It can usually be taken as a broadly linear function but can be noticeably non-linear at the temperature extremes.
[src:chemical-energy/capacitor-p01] The temperature coefficient may be positive or negative, depending mostly on the dielectric material.
[src:chemical-energy/capacitor-p01] Some, designated C0G/NP0, but called **NPO**, have a somewhat negative coefficient at one temperature, positive at another, and zero in between.
[src:chemical-energy/capacitor-p01] Such components may be specified for temperature-critical circuits.
[src:chemical-energy/capacitor-p01] Capacitors, especially ceramic capacitors, and older designs such as paper capacitors, can absorb sound waves resulting in a microphonic effect.
[src:chemical-energy/capacitor-p01] Vibration moves the plates, causing the capacitance to vary, in turn inducing AC current.
[src:chemical-energy/capacitor-p01] Some dielectrics also generate piezoelectricity.
[src:chemical-energy/capacitor-p01] The resulting interference is especially problematic in audio applications, potentially causing feedback or unintended recording.
[src:chemical-energy/capacitor-p01] In the reverse microphonic effect, the varying electric field between the capacitor plates exerts a physical force, moving them as a speaker.
[src:chemical-energy/capacitor-p01] This can generate audible sound, but drains energy and stresses the dielectric and the electrolyte, if any.
[src:chemical-energy/capacitor-p01] Current reversal occurs when the current changes direction.
[src:chemical-energy/capacitor-p01] Voltage reversal is the change of polarity in a circuit.
[src:chemical-energy/capacitor-p01] Reversal is generally described as the percentage of the maximum rated voltage that reverses polarity.
[src:chemical-energy/capacitor-p01] In DC circuits, this is usually less than 100%, often in the range of 0 to 90%, whereas AC circuits experience 100% reversal.
[src:chemical-energy/capacitor-p01] In DC circuits and pulsed circuits, current and voltage reversal are affected by the damping of the system.
[src:chemical-energy/capacitor-p01] Voltage reversal is encountered in RLC circuits that are underdamped.
[src:chemical-energy/capacitor-p01] The current and voltage reverse direction, forming a harmonic oscillator between the inductance and capacitance.
[src:chemical-energy/capacitor-p01] The current and voltage tends to oscillate and may reverse direction several times, with each peak being lower than the previous, until the system reaches an equilibrium.
[src:chemical-energy/capacitor-p01] In comparison, critically damped or overdamped systems usually do not experience a voltage reversal.
[src:chemical-energy/capacitor-p01] Reversal is also encountered in AC circuits, where the peak current is equal in each direction.
[src:chemical-energy/capacitor-p01] For maximum life, capacitors usually need to be able to handle the maximum amount of reversal that a system may experience.
[src:chemical-energy/capacitor-p01] An AC circuit experiences 100% voltage reversal, while underdamped DC circuits experience less than 100%.
[src:chemical-energy/capacitor-p01] Reversal creates excess electric fields in the dielectric, causes excess heating of both the dielectric and the conductors, and can dramatically shorten the life expectancy of the capacitor.
[src:chemical-energy/capacitor-p01] Reversal ratings often affect the design considerations for the capacitor, from the choice of dielectric materials and voltage ratings to the types of internal connections used.
[src:chemical-energy/capacitor-p01] Capacitors made with any type of dielectric material show some level of "dielectric absorption" or "soakage".
[src:chemical-energy/capacitor-p01] On discharging a capacitor and disconnecting it, after a short time it may develop a voltage due to hysteresis in the dielectric.
[src:chemical-energy/capacitor-p01] This effect is objectionable in applications such as precision sample and hold circuits or timing circuits.
[src:chemical-energy/capacitor-p01] The level of absorption depends on many factors, from design considerations to charging time, since the absorption is a time-dependent process.
[src:chemical-energy/capacitor-p01] However, the primary factor is the type of dielectric material.
[src:chemical-energy/capacitor-p01] Capacitors such as tantalum electrolytic or polysulfone film exhibit relatively high absorption, while polystyrene or Teflon allow very small levels of absorption.
[src:chemical-energy/capacitor-p01] In some capacitors where dangerous voltages and energies exist, such as in flashtubes, television sets, microwave ovens and defibrillators, the dielectric absorption can recharge the capacitor to hazardous voltages after it has been shorted or discharged.
[src:chemical-energy/capacitor-p01] Any capacitor containing over 10 joules of energy is generally considered hazardous, while 50 joules or higher is potentially lethal.
[src:chemical-energy/capacitor-p01] A capacitor may regain anywhere from 0.01 to 20% of its original charge over a period of several minutes, allowing a seemingly safe capacitor to become surprisingly dangerous.
[src:chemical-energy/capacitor-p01] No material is a perfect insulator, thus all dielectrics allow some small level of current to leak through, which can be measured with a megohmmeter.
[src:chemical-energy/capacitor-p01] Leakage is equivalent to a resistor in parallel with the capacitor.
[src:chemical-energy/capacitor-p01] Constant exposure to factors such as heat, mechanical stress, or humidity can cause the dielectric to deteriorate resulting in excessive leakage, a problem often seen in older vacuum tube circuits, particularly where oiled paper and foil capacitors were used.
[src:chemical-energy/capacitor-p01] In many vacuum tube circuits, interstage coupling capacitors are used to conduct a varying signal from the plate of one tube to the grid circuit of the next stage.
[src:chemical-energy/capacitor-p01] A leaky capacitor can cause the grid circuit voltage to be raised from its normal bias setting, causing excessive current or signal distortion in the downstream tube.
[src:chemical-energy/capacitor-p01] In power amplifiers this can cause the plates to glow red, or current limiting resistors to overheat, even fail.
[src:chemical-energy/capacitor-p01] Similar considerations apply to component fabricated solid-state (transistor) amplifiers, but, owing to lower heat production and the use of modern polyester dielectric-barriers, this once-common problem has become relatively rare.
[src:chemical-energy/capacitor-p01] Aluminum electrolytic capacitors are *conditioned* when manufactured by applying a voltage sufficient to initiate the proper internal chemical state.
[src:chemical-energy/capacitor-p01] This state is maintained by regular use of the equipment.
[src:chemical-energy/capacitor-p01] If a system using electrolytic capacitors is unused for a long period of time it can lose its conditioning.
[src:chemical-energy/capacitor-p01] Sometimes they fail with a short circuit when next operated.
[src:chemical-energy/capacitor-p01] All capacitors have varying lifespans, depending upon their construction, operational conditions, and environmental conditions.
[src:chemical-energy/capacitor-p01] Solid-state ceramic capacitors generally have very long lives under normal use, which has little dependency on factors such as vibration or ambient temperature, but factors like humidity, mechanical stress, and fatigue play a primary role in their failure.
[src:chemical-energy/capacitor-p01] Some capacitors may experience a gradual loss of capacitance, increased leakage or an increase in equivalent series resistance (ESR), while others may fail suddenly or even catastrophically.
[src:chemical-energy/capacitor-p01] For example, metal-film capacitors are more prone to damage from stress and humidity, but will self-heal when a breakdown in the dielectric occurs.
[src:chemical-energy/capacitor-p01] The formation of a glow discharge at the point of failure prevents arcing by vaporizing the metallic film in that spot, neutralizing any short circuit with minimal loss in capacitance.
[src:chemical-energy/capacitor-p01] When enough pinholes accumulate in the film, a total failure occurs in a metal-film capacitor, generally happening suddenly without warning.
[src:chemical-energy/capacitor-p01] Electrolytic capacitors generally have the shortest lifespans.
[src:chemical-energy/capacitor-p01] Electrolytic capacitors are affected very little by vibration or humidity, but factors such as ambient and operational temperatures play a large role in their failure, which gradually occur as an increase in ESR (up to 300%) and as much as a 20% decrease in capacitance.
[src:chemical-energy/capacitor-p01] The capacitors contain electrolytes which will eventually diffuse through the seals and evaporate.
[src:chemical-energy/capacitor-p01] An increase in temperature also increases internal pressure, and increases the reaction rate of the chemicals.
[src:chemical-energy/capacitor-p01] Manufacturers often use this equation to supply an expected lifespan, in hours, for electrolytic capacitors when used at their designed operating temperature, which is affected by both ambient temperature, ESR, and ripple current.
[src:chemical-energy/capacitor-p01] However, these ideal conditions may not exist in every use.
[src:chemical-energy/capacitor-p02] Practical capacitors are available commercially in many different forms.
[src:chemical-energy/capacitor-p02] The type of internal dielectric, the structure of the plates and the device packaging all strongly affect the characteristics of the capacitor, and its applications.
[src:chemical-energy/capacitor-p02] Values available range from very low (picofarad range; while arbitrarily low values are in principle possible, stray (parasitic) capacitance in any circuit is the limiting factor) to about 5 kF supercapacitors.
[src:chemical-energy/capacitor-p02] Above approximately 1 microfarad electrolytic capacitors are usually used because of their small size and low cost compared with other types, unless their relatively poor stability, life and polarised nature make them unsuitable.
[src:chemical-energy/capacitor-p02] Very high capacity supercapacitors use a porous carbon-based electrode material.
[src:chemical-energy/capacitor-p02] Most capacitors have a dielectric spacer, which increases their capacitance compared to air or a vacuum.
[src:chemical-energy/capacitor-p02] In order to maximise the charge that a capacitor can hold, the dielectric material needs to have as high a permittivity as possible, while also having as high a breakdown voltage as possible.
[src:chemical-energy/capacitor-p02] The dielectric also needs to have as low a loss with frequency as possible.
[src:chemical-energy/capacitor-p02] However, low value capacitors are available with a high vacuum between their plates to allow extremely high voltage operation and low losses.
[src:chemical-energy/capacitor-p02] Variable capacitors with their plates open to the atmosphere were commonly used in radio tuning circuits.
[src:chemical-energy/capacitor-p02] Later designs use polymer foil dielectric between the moving and stationary plates, with no significant air space between the plates.
[src:chemical-energy/capacitor-p02] Several solid dielectrics are available, including paper, plastic, glass, mica and ceramic.
[src:chemical-energy/capacitor-p02] Paper was used extensively in older capacitors and offers relatively high voltage performance.
[src:chemical-energy/capacitor-p02] However, paper absorbs moisture, and has been largely replaced by plastic film capacitors.
[src:chemical-energy/capacitor-p02] Large plastic film capacitors are used extensively in suppression circuits, motor start circuits, and power-factor correction circuits.
[src:chemical-energy/capacitor-p02] Ceramic capacitors are generally small, cheap and useful for high frequency applications, although their capacitance varies strongly with voltage and temperature and they age poorly.
[src:chemical-energy/capacitor-p02] They can also suffer from the piezoelectric effect.
[src:chemical-energy/capacitor-p02] Ceramic capacitors are broadly categorized as class 1 dielectrics, which have predictable variation of capacitance with temperature or class 2 dielectrics, which can operate at higher voltage.
[src:chemical-energy/capacitor-p02] Modern multilayer ceramics are usually quite small, but some types have inherently wide value tolerances, microphonic issues, and are usually physically brittle.
[src:chemical-energy/capacitor-p02] Glass and mica capacitors are extremely reliable, stable and tolerant to high temperatures and voltages, but are too expensive for most mainstream applications.
[src:chemical-energy/capacitor-p02] Electrolytic capacitors use an aluminum or tantalum plate with an oxide dielectric layer.
[src:chemical-energy/capacitor-p02] The second electrode is a liquid electrolyte, connected to the circuit by another foil plate.
[src:chemical-energy/capacitor-p02] Electrolytic capacitors offer very high capacitance but suffer from poor tolerances, high instability, gradual loss of capacitance especially when subjected to heat, and high leakage current.
[src:chemical-energy/capacitor-p02] Poor quality capacitors may leak electrolyte, which is harmful to printed circuit boards.
[src:chemical-energy/capacitor-p02] The conductivity of the electrolyte drops at low temperatures, which increases equivalent series resistance.
[src:chemical-energy/capacitor-p02] While widely used for power-supply conditioning, poor high-frequency characteristics make them unsuitable for many applications.
[src:chemical-energy/capacitor-p02] Electrolytic capacitors suffer from self-degradation if unused for a period (around a year), and when full power is applied may short circuit, permanently damaging the capacitor and usually blowing a fuse or causing failure of rectifier diodes.
[src:chemical-energy/capacitor-p02] For example, in older equipment, this may cause arcing in rectifier tubes.
[src:chemical-energy/capacitor-p02] They can be restored before use by gradually applying the operating voltage, often performed on antique vacuum tube equipment over a period of thirty minutes by using a variable transformer to supply AC power.
[src:chemical-energy/capacitor-p02] The use of this technique may be less satisfactory for some solid state equipment, which may be damaged by operation below its normal power range, requiring that the power supply first be isolated from the consuming circuits.
[src:chemical-energy/capacitor-p02] Such remedies may not be applicable to modern high-frequency power supplies as these produce full output voltage even with reduced input.
[src:chemical-energy/capacitor-p02] Tantalum capacitors offer better frequency and temperature characteristics than aluminum, but higher dielectric absorption and leakage.
[src:chemical-energy/capacitor-p02] Polymer capacitors (OS-CON, OC-CON, KO, AO) use solid conductive polymer (or polymerized organic semiconductor) as electrolyte and offer longer life and lower ESR at higher cost than standard electrolytic capacitors.
[src:chemical-energy/capacitor-p02] A feedthrough capacitor is a component that, while not serving as its main use, has capacitance and is used to conduct signals through a conductive sheet.
[src:chemical-energy/capacitor-p02] Several other types of capacitor are available for specialist applications.
[src:chemical-energy/capacitor-p02] Supercapacitors store large amounts of energy.
[src:chemical-energy/capacitor-p02] Supercapacitors made from carbon aerogel, carbon nanotubes, or highly porous electrode materials, offer extremely high capacitance (up to 5 kF as of 2010) and can be used in some applications instead of rechargeable batteries.
[src:chemical-energy/capacitor-p02] Alternating current capacitors are specifically designed to work on line (mains) voltage AC power circuits.
[src:chemical-energy/capacitor-p02] They are commonly used in electric motor circuits and are often designed to handle large currents, so they tend to be physically large.
[src:chemical-energy/capacitor-p02] They are usually ruggedly packaged, often in metal cases that can be easily grounded/earthed.
[src:chemical-energy/capacitor-p02] They also are designed with direct current breakdown voltages of at least five times the maximum AC voltage.
[src:chemical-energy/capacitor-p02] The dielectric constant for a number of very useful dielectrics changes as a function of the applied electrical field, for example ferroelectric materials, so the capacitance for these devices is more complex.
[src:chemical-energy/capacitor-p02] This field polarizes the dielectric, which polarization, in the case of a ferroelectric, is a nonlinear *S*-shaped function of the electric field, which, in the case of a large area parallel plate device, translates into a capacitance that is a nonlinear function of the voltage.
[src:chemical-energy/capacitor-p02] Corresponding to the voltage-dependent capacitance, to charge the capacitor to voltage V an integral relation is found: $Q=\int _{0}^{V}C(V)\mathop {} \!\mathrm {d} V$ which agrees with *Q* = *CV* only when C does not depend on voltage V.
[src:chemical-energy/capacitor-p02] The nonlinear capacitance of a microscope probe scanned along a ferroelectric surface is used to study the domain structure of ferroelectric materials.
[src:chemical-energy/capacitor-p02] Another example of voltage dependent capacitance occurs in semiconductor devices such as semiconductor diodes, where the voltage dependence stems not from a change in dielectric constant but in a voltage dependence of the spacing between the charges on the two sides of the capacitor.
[src:chemical-energy/capacitor-p02] This effect is intentionally exploited in diode-like devices known as varicaps.
[src:chemical-energy/capacitor-p02] If a capacitor is driven with a time-varying voltage that changes rapidly enough, at some frequency the polarization of the dielectric cannot follow the voltage.
[src:chemical-energy/capacitor-p02] As an example of the origin of this mechanism, the internal microscopic dipoles contributing to the dielectric constant cannot move instantly, and so as frequency of an applied alternating voltage increases, the dipole response is limited and the dielectric constant diminishes.
[src:chemical-energy/capacitor-p02] A changing dielectric constant with frequency is referred to as dielectric dispersion, and is governed by dielectric relaxation processes, such as Debye relaxation.
[src:chemical-energy/capacitor-p02] indicating the lag in response by the time dependence of *εr*, calculated in principle from an underlying microscopic analysis, for example, of the dipole behavior in the dielectric.
[src:chemical-energy/capacitor-p02] See, for example, linear response function.
[src:chemical-energy/capacitor-p02] The integral extends over the entire past history up to the present time.
[src:chemical-energy/capacitor-p02] where *ε*r(*ω*) is now a complex function, with an imaginary part related to absorption of energy from the field by the medium.
[src:chemical-energy/capacitor-p02] The capacitance, being proportional to the dielectric constant, also exhibits this frequency behavior.
[src:chemical-energy/capacitor-p02] (Measurement "without the dielectric" in principle means measurement in free space, an unattainable goal inasmuch as even the quantum vacuum is predicted to exhibit nonideal behavior, such as dichroism.
[src:chemical-energy/capacitor-p02] Using this measurement method, the dielectric constant may exhibit a resonance at certain frequencies corresponding to characteristic response frequencies (excitation energies) of contributors to the dielectric constant.
[src:chemical-energy/capacitor-p02] These resonances are the basis for a number of experimental techniques for detecting defects.
[src:chemical-energy/capacitor-p02] The *conductance method* measures absorption as a function of frequency.
[src:chemical-energy/capacitor-p02] Alternatively, the time response of the capacitance can be used directly, as in *deep-level transient spectroscopy*.
[src:chemical-energy/capacitor-p02] Another example of frequency dependent capacitance occurs with MOS capacitors, where the slow generation of minority carriers means that at high frequencies the capacitance measures only the majority carrier response, while at low frequencies both types of carrier respond.
[src:chemical-energy/capacitor-p02] At optical frequencies, in semiconductors the dielectric constant exhibits structure related to the band structure of the solid.
[src:chemical-energy/capacitor-p02] Sophisticated modulation spectroscopy measurement methods based upon modulating the crystal structure by pressure or by other stresses and observing the related changes in absorption or reflection of light have advanced our knowledge of these materials.
[src:chemical-energy/capacitor-p02] The arrangement of plates and dielectric has many variations in different styles depending on the desired ratings of the capacitor.
[src:chemical-energy/capacitor-p02] For small values of capacitance (microfarads and less), ceramic disks use metallic coatings, with wire leads bonded to the coating.
[src:chemical-energy/capacitor-p02] Larger values can be made by multiple stacks of plates and disks.
[src:chemical-energy/capacitor-p02] Larger value capacitors usually use a metal foil or metal film layer deposited on the surface of a dielectric film to make the plates, and a dielectric film of impregnated paper or plastic – these are rolled up to save space.
[src:chemical-energy/capacitor-p02] To reduce the series resistance and inductance for long plates, the plates and dielectric are staggered so that connection is made at the common edge of the rolled-up plates, not at the ends of the foil or metalized film strips that comprise the plates.
[src:chemical-energy/capacitor-p02] The assembly is encased to prevent moisture entering the dielectric – early radio equipment used a cardboard tube sealed with wax.
[src:chemical-energy/capacitor-p02] Modern paper or film dielectric capacitors are dipped in a hard thermoplastic.
[src:chemical-energy/capacitor-p02] Large capacitors for high-voltage use may have the roll form compressed to fit into a rectangular metal case, with bolted terminals and bushings for connections.
[src:chemical-energy/capacitor-p02] The dielectric in larger capacitors is often impregnated with a liquid to improve its properties.
[src:chemical-energy/capacitor-p02] Capacitors may have their connecting leads arranged in many configurations, for example axially or radially.
[src:chemical-energy/capacitor-p02] "Axial" means that the leads are on a common axis, typically the axis of the capacitor's cylindrical body – the leads extend from opposite ends.
[src:chemical-energy/capacitor-p02] Radial leads are rarely aligned along radii of the body's circle, so the term is conventional.
[src:chemical-energy/capacitor-p02] The leads (until bent) are usually in planes parallel to that of the flat body of the capacitor, and extend in the same direction; they are often parallel as manufactured.
[src:chemical-energy/capacitor-p02] Small, cheap discoidal ceramic capacitors have existed from the 1930s onward, and remain in widespread use.
[src:chemical-energy/capacitor-p02] After the 1980s, surface mount packages for capacitors have been widely used.
[src:chemical-energy/capacitor-p02] These packages are extremely small and lack connecting leads, allowing them to be soldered directly onto the surface of printed circuit boards.
[src:chemical-energy/capacitor-p02] Surface mount components avoid undesirable high-frequency effects due to the leads and simplify automated assembly, although manual handling is made difficult due to their small size.
[src:chemical-energy/capacitor-p02] Mechanically controlled variable capacitors allow the plate spacing to be adjusted, for example by rotating or sliding a set of movable plates into alignment with a set of stationary plates.
[src:chemical-energy/capacitor-p02] Low cost variable capacitors squeeze together alternating layers of aluminum and plastic with a screw.
[src:chemical-energy/capacitor-p02] Electrical control of capacitance is achievable with varactors (or varicaps), which are reverse-biased semiconductor diodes whose depletion region width varies with applied voltage.
[src:chemical-energy/capacitor-p02] They are used in phase-locked loops, amongst other applications.
[src:chemical-energy/capacitor-p02] Most capacitors have designations printed on their bodies to indicate their electrical characteristics.
[src:chemical-energy/capacitor-p02] Larger capacitors, such as electrolytic types usually display the capacitance as value with explicit unit, for example, *220 μF*.
[src:chemical-energy/capacitor-p02] For typographical reasons, some manufacturers print *MF* on capacitors to indicate microfarads (μF).
[src:chemical-energy/capacitor-p02] Smaller capacitors, such as ceramic types, often use a shorthand-notation consisting of three digits and an optional letter, where the digits (*XYZ*) denote the capacitance in picofarad (pF), calculated as *XY* × 10*Z*, and the letter indicating the tolerance.
[src:chemical-energy/capacitor-p02] Common tolerances are ±5%, ±10%, and ±20%, denoted as J, K, and M, respectively.
[src:chemical-energy/capacitor-p02] A capacitor may also be labeled with its working voltage, temperature, and other relevant characteristics.
[src:chemical-energy/capacitor-p02] Example: A capacitor labeled or designated as *473K 330V* has a capacitance of 47×103 pF = 47 nF (±10%) with a maximum working voltage of 330 V.
[src:chemical-energy/capacitor-p02] The working voltage of a capacitor is nominally the highest voltage that may be applied across it without undue risk of breaking down the dielectric layer.
[src:chemical-energy/capacitor-p02] The code consists of an uppercase letter denoting the two significant digits of the value followed by a digit indicating the multiplier.
[src:chemical-energy/capacitor-p02] The EIA standard also defines a number of lowercase letters to specify a number of values not found in E24.
[src:chemical-energy/capacitor-p02] The RKM code following IEC 60062 and BS 1852 is a notation to state a capacitor's value in a circuit diagram.
[src:chemical-energy/capacitor-p02] It avoids using a decimal separator and replaces the decimal separator with the SI prefix symbol for the particular value (and the letter F for weight 1).
[src:chemical-energy/capacitor-p02] The code is also used for part markings.
[src:chemical-energy/capacitor-p02] In texts prior to the 1960s and on some capacitor packages until more recently, obsolete capacitance units were utilized in electronic books, magazines, and electronics catalogs.
[src:chemical-energy/capacitor-p02] The old units "mfd" and "mf" meant *microfarad* (μF); and the old units "mmfd", "mmf", "uuf", "μμf", "pfd" meant *picofarad* (pF); but they are rarely used any more.
[src:chemical-energy/capacitor-p02] Also, "Micromicrofarad" or "micro-microfarad" are obsolete units that are found in some older texts that is equivalent to *picofarad* (pF).
[src:chemical-energy/capacitor-p02] A capacitor can store electric energy when disconnected from its charging circuit, so it can be used like a temporary battery, or like other types of rechargeable energy storage system.
[src:chemical-energy/capacitor-p02] Capacitors are commonly used in electronic devices to maintain power supply while batteries are being changed.
[src:chemical-energy/capacitor-p02] A capacitor can facilitate conversion of kinetic energy of charged particles into electric energy and store it.
[src:chemical-energy/capacitor-p02] There are tradeoffs between capacitors and batteries as storage devices.
[src:chemical-energy/capacitor-p02] Without external resistors or inductors, capacitors can generally release their stored energy in a very short time compared to batteries.
[src:chemical-energy/capacitor-p02] Conversely, batteries can hold a far greater charge per their size.
[src:chemical-energy/capacitor-p02] Conventional capacitors provide less than 360 joules per kilogram of specific energy, whereas a conventional alkaline battery has a density of 590 kJ/kg.
[src:chemical-energy/capacitor-p02] There is an intermediate solution: supercapacitors, which can accept and deliver charge much faster than batteries, and tolerate many more charge and discharge cycles than rechargeable batteries.
[src:chemical-energy/capacitor-p02] They are, however, 10 times larger than conventional batteries for a given charge.
[src:chemical-energy/capacitor-p02] On the other hand, it has been shown that the amount of charge stored in the dielectric layer of the thin film capacitor can be equal to, or can even exceed, the amount of charge stored on its plates.
[src:chemical-energy/capacitor-p02] In car audio systems, large capacitors store energy for the amplifier to use on demand.
[src:chemical-energy/capacitor-p02] Also, for a flash tube, a capacitor is used to hold the high voltage.
[src:chemical-energy/capacitor-p02] In the 1930s, John Atanasoff applied the principle of energy storage in capacitors to construct dynamic digital memories for the first binary computers that used electron tubes for logic.
[src:chemical-energy/capacitor-p02] Pulsed power is used in many applications to increase the power intensity (watts) of a volume of energy (joules) by releasing that volume within a very short time.
[src:chemical-energy/capacitor-p02] Pulses in the nanosecond range and powers in the gigawatts are achievable.
[src:chemical-energy/capacitor-p02] Short pulses often require specially constructed, low-inductance, high-voltage capacitors that are often used in large groups (*capacitor banks*) to supply huge pulses of current for many pulsed power applications.
[src:chemical-energy/capacitor-p02] These include electromagnetic forming, Marx generators, pulsed lasers (especially TEA lasers), pulse forming networks, radar, fusion research, and particle accelerators.
[src:chemical-energy/capacitor-p02] Large capacitor banks (reservoir) are used as energy sources for the exploding-bridgewire detonators or slapper detonators in nuclear weapons and other specialty weapons.
[src:chemical-energy/capacitor-p02] Experimental work is under way using banks of capacitors as power sources for electromagnetic armour and electromagnetic railguns and coilguns.
[src:chemical-energy/capacitor-p02] Reservoir capacitors are used in power supplies where they smooth the output of a full or half wave rectifier.
[src:chemical-energy/capacitor-p02] They can also be used in charge pump circuits as the energy storage element in the generation of higher voltages than the input voltage.
[src:chemical-energy/capacitor-p02] Capacitors are connected in parallel with the power circuits of most electronic devices and larger systems (such as factories) to shunt away and conceal current fluctuations from the primary power source to provide a "clean" power supply for signal or control circuits.
[src:chemical-energy/capacitor-p02] Audio equipment, for example, uses several capacitors in this way, to shunt away power line hum before it gets into the signal circuitry.
[src:chemical-energy/capacitor-p02] The capacitors act as a local reserve for the DC power source, and bypass AC currents from the power supply.
[src:chemical-energy/capacitor-p02] This is used in car audio applications, when a stiffening capacitor compensates for the inductance and resistance of the leads to the lead–acid car battery.
[src:chemical-energy/capacitor-p02] In electric power distribution, capacitors are used for power-factor correction.
[src:chemical-energy/capacitor-p02] Such capacitors often come as three capacitors connected as a three phase load.
[src:chemical-energy/capacitor-p02] Usually, the values of these capacitors are not given in farads but rather as a reactive power in volt-amperes reactive (var).
[src:chemical-energy/capacitor-p02] The purpose is to counteract inductive loading from devices like electric motors and transmission lines to make the load appear to be mostly resistive.
[src:chemical-energy/capacitor-p02] Individual motor or lamp loads may have capacitors for power-factor correction, or larger sets of capacitors (usually with automatic switching devices) may be installed at a load center within a building or in a large utility substation.
[src:chemical-energy/capacitor-p02] Because capacitors pass AC but block DC signals (when charged up to the applied DC voltage), they are often used to separate the AC and DC components of a signal.
[src:chemical-energy/capacitor-p02] This method is known as *AC coupling* or "capacitive coupling".
[src:chemical-energy/capacitor-p02] Here, a large value of capacitance, whose value need not be accurately controlled, but whose reactance is small at the signal frequency, is employed.
[src:chemical-energy/capacitor-p02] A decoupling capacitor is a capacitor used to protect one part of a circuit from the effect of another, for instance to suppress noise or transients.
[src:chemical-energy/capacitor-p02] Noise caused by other circuit elements is shunted through the capacitor, reducing the effect they have on the rest of the circuit.
[src:chemical-energy/capacitor-p02] It is most commonly used between the power supply and ground.
[src:chemical-energy/capacitor-p02] An alternative name is *bypass capacitor* as it is used to bypass the power supply or other high impedance component of a circuit.
[src:chemical-energy/capacitor-p02] Decoupling capacitors need not always be discrete components.
[src:chemical-energy/capacitor-p02] Capacitors used in these applications may be built into a printed circuit board, between the various layers.
[src:chemical-energy/capacitor-p02] These are often referred to as embedded capacitors.
[src:chemical-energy/capacitor-p02] The layers in the board contributing to the capacitive properties also function as power and ground planes, and have a dielectric in between them, enabling them to operate as a parallel plate capacitor.
[src:chemical-energy/capacitor-p02] When an inductive circuit is opened, the current through the inductance collapses quickly, creating a large voltage across the open circuit of the switch or relay.
[src:chemical-energy/capacitor-p02] If the inductance is large enough, the energy may generate a spark, causing the contact points to oxidize, deteriorate, or sometimes weld together, or destroying a solid-state switch.
[src:chemical-energy/capacitor-p02] A snubber capacitor across the newly opened circuit creates a path for this impulse to bypass the contact points, thereby preserving their life; these were commonly found in contact breaker ignition systems, for instance.
[src:chemical-energy/capacitor-p02] Similarly, in smaller scale circuits, the spark may not be enough to damage the switch but may still radiate undesirable radio frequency interference (RFI), which a filter capacitor absorbs.
[src:chemical-energy/capacitor-p02] Snubber capacitors are usually employed with a low-value resistor in series, to dissipate energy and minimize RFI.
[src:chemical-energy/capacitor-p02] Such resistor-capacitor combinations are available in a single package.
[src:chemical-energy/capacitor-p02] Capacitors are also used in parallel with interrupting units of a high-voltage circuit breaker to equally distribute the voltage between these units.
[src:chemical-energy/capacitor-p02] In schematic diagrams, a capacitor used primarily for DC charge storage is often drawn vertically in circuit diagrams with the lower, more negative, plate drawn as an arc.
[src:chemical-energy/capacitor-p02] The straight plate indicates the positive terminal of the device, if it is polarized (see electrolytic capacitor).
[src:chemical-energy/capacitor-p02] In single phase squirrel cage motors, the primary winding within the motor housing is not capable of starting a rotational motion on the rotor, but is capable of sustaining one.
[src:chemical-energy/capacitor-p02] To start the motor, a secondary "start" winding has a series non-polarized *starting capacitor* to introduce a lead in the sinusoidal current.
[src:chemical-energy/capacitor-p02] When the secondary (start) winding is placed at an angle with respect to the primary (run) winding, a rotating electric field is created.
[src:chemical-energy/capacitor-p02] The force of the rotational field is not constant, but is sufficient to start the rotor spinning.
[src:chemical-energy/capacitor-p02] When the rotor comes close to operating speed, a centrifugal switch (or current-sensitive relay in series with the main winding) disconnects the capacitor.
[src:chemical-energy/capacitor-p02] The start capacitor is typically mounted to the side of the motor housing.
[src:chemical-energy/capacitor-p02] These are called capacitor-start motors, that have relatively high starting torque.
[src:chemical-energy/capacitor-p02] Typically they can have up-to four times as much starting torque as a split-phase motor and are used on applications such as compressors, pressure washers and any small device requiring high starting torques.
[src:chemical-energy/capacitor-p02] Capacitor-run induction motors have a permanently connected phase-shifting capacitor in series with a second winding.
[src:chemical-energy/capacitor-p02] The motor is much like a two-phase induction motor.
[src:chemical-energy/capacitor-p02] Motor-starting capacitors are typically non-polarized electrolytic types, while running capacitors are conventional paper or plastic film dielectric types.
[src:chemical-energy/capacitor-p02] The energy stored in a capacitor can be used to represent information, either in binary form, as in DRAMs, or in analogue form, as in analog sampled filters and CCDs.
[src:chemical-energy/capacitor-p02] Capacitors can be used in analog circuits as components of integrators or more complex filters and in negative feedback loop stabilization.
[src:chemical-energy/capacitor-p02] Signal processing circuits also use capacitors to integrate a current signal.
[src:chemical-energy/capacitor-p02] Capacitors and inductors are applied together in tuned circuits to select information in particular frequency bands.
[src:chemical-energy/capacitor-p02] For example, radio receivers rely on variable capacitors to tune the station frequency.
[src:chemical-energy/capacitor-p02] Speakers use passive analog crossovers, and analog equalizers use capacitors to select different audio bands.
[src:chemical-energy/capacitor-p02] The resonant frequency *f* of a tuned circuit is a function of the inductance (*L*) and capacitance (*C*) in series, and is given by: $f={\frac {1}{2\pi {\sqrt {LC}}}}$ where L is in henries and C is in farads.
[src:chemical-energy/capacitor-p02] Most capacitors are designed to maintain a fixed physical structure.
[src:chemical-energy/capacitor-p02] However, various factors can change the structure of the capacitor, and the resulting change in capacitance can be used to sense those factors.
[src:chemical-energy/capacitor-p02] Capacitors with an exposed and porous dielectric can be used to measure humidity in air.
[src:chemical-energy/capacitor-p02] ; as the fuel covers more of a pair of plates, the circuit capacitance increases.
[src:chemical-energy/capacitor-p02] Squeezing the dielectric can change a capacitor at a few tens of bar pressure sufficiently that it can be used as a pressure sensor.
[src:chemical-energy/capacitor-p02] A selected, but otherwise standard, polymer dielectric capacitor, when immersed in a compatible gas or liquid, can work usefully as a very low cost pressure sensor up to many hundreds of bar.
[src:chemical-energy/capacitor-p02] Capacitors with a flexible plate can be used to measure strain or pressure.
[src:chemical-energy/capacitor-p02] use pressure-sensing diaphragms, which form a capacitor plate of an oscillator circuit.
[src:chemical-energy/capacitor-p02] , where one plate is moved by air pressure, relative to the fixed position of the other plate.
[src:chemical-energy/capacitor-p02] capacitors etched on a chip to measure the magnitude and direction of the acceleration vector.
[src:chemical-energy/capacitor-p02] deployment, and in many other applications.
[src:chemical-energy/capacitor-p02] musical instrument by moving their hand since this changes the effective capacitance between the user's hand and the antenna.
[src:chemical-energy/capacitor-p02] are used on many consumer electronic products.
[src:chemical-energy/capacitor-p02] A capacitor can possess spring-like qualities in an oscillator circuit.
[src:chemical-energy/capacitor-p02] In the image example, a capacitor acts to influence the biasing voltage at the npn transistor's base.
[src:chemical-energy/capacitor-p02] The resistance values of the voltage-divider resistors and the capacitance value of the capacitor together control the oscillatory frequency.
[src:chemical-energy/capacitor-p02] A light-emitting capacitor is made from a dielectric that uses phosphorescence to produce light.
[src:chemical-energy/capacitor-p02] If one of the conductive plates is made with a transparent material, the light is visible.
[src:chemical-energy/capacitor-p02] Light-emitting capacitors are used in the construction of electroluminescent panels, for applications such as backlighting for laptop computers.
[src:chemical-energy/capacitor-p02] In this case, the entire panel is a capacitor used for the purpose of generating light.
[src:chemical-energy/capacitor-p02] The hazards posed by a capacitor are usually determined by the amount of energy stored, which can cause electrical burns or heart fibrillation.
[src:chemical-energy/capacitor-p02] Factors such as voltage and chassis material are of secondary consideration, which are more related to how easily a shock can be initiated rather than how much damage can occur.
[src:chemical-energy/capacitor-p02] Shocks over ten joules generally damage skin, and are considered hazardous.
[src:chemical-energy/capacitor-p02] Any capacitor that can store 50 joules or more is considered potentially lethal.
[src:chemical-energy/capacitor-p02] Capacitors may retain a charge long after power is removed from a circuit; this charge can cause dangerous or fatal shocks or damage connected equipment.
[src:chemical-energy/capacitor-p02] For example, the flash of a disposable camera has a photoflash capacitor that may contain over 15 joules of energy and be charged to over 300 volts.
[src:chemical-energy/capacitor-p02] Service procedures for electronic devices usually include instructions to discharge large or high-voltage capacitors.
[src:chemical-energy/capacitor-p02] Larger capacitors may have built-in discharge resistors to dissipate stored energy to a safe level within a few seconds after power is removed.
[src:chemical-energy/capacitor-p02] High-voltage capacitors are stored with the terminals shorted, as protection from potentially dangerous voltages due to dielectric absorption or from transient voltages the capacitor may pick up from static charges or passing weather events.
[src:chemical-energy/capacitor-p02] Some old, large oil-filled paper or plastic film capacitors contain polychlorinated biphenyls (PCBs) which can leak into groundwater from landfills.
[src:chemical-energy/capacitor-p02] Capacitors containing PCBs were labelled as containing "Askarel" and several other trade names.
[src:chemical-energy/capacitor-p02] PCB-filled paper capacitors are found in pre-1975 fluorescent lamp ballasts, and other applications.
[src:chemical-energy/capacitor-p02] Such capacitors may be sealed in a metal can with ceramic feed-through connectors.
[src:chemical-energy/capacitor-p02] Capacitors may catastrophically fail when subjected to voltages or currents beyond their rating, or in case of polarized capacitors, applied in a reverse polarity.
[src:chemical-energy/capacitor-p02] Failures may create arcing that heats and vaporizes the dielectric fluid, causing a build up of pressurized gas that may result in swelling, rupture, or an explosion.
[src:chemical-energy/capacitor-p02] Larger capacitors may have vents or similar mechanism to release of pressure in the event of failure.
[src:chemical-energy/capacitor-p02] Capacitors used in RF or sustained high-current applications can overheat, especially in the center of the capacitor rolls.
[src:chemical-energy/capacitor-p02] Capacitors used within high-energy capacitor banks can violently explode when a short in one capacitor causes sudden dumping of energy stored in the rest of the bank into the failing unit.
[src:chemical-energy/capacitor-p02] High voltage vacuum capacitors can generate soft X-rays even during normal operation.
[src:chemical-energy/capacitor-p02] Proper containment, fusing, and preventive maintenance can help to minimize these hazards.
[src:chemical-energy/capacitor-p02] High-voltage capacitors may benefit from a pre-charge to limit in-rush currents at power-up of high voltage direct current (HVDC) circuits.
[src:chemical-energy/capacitor-p02] This extends the life of the component and may mitigate high-voltage hazards.
[src:chemical-energy/chemical-energy] Energy that can be released or absorbed because of a reaction between chemical substances is equal to the difference between the energy content of the products and the reactants, if the initial and final temperature is the same.
[src:chemical-energy/chemical-energy] This change in energy can be estimated from the bond energies of the reactants and products.
[src:chemical-energy/chemical-energy] It can also be calculated from $\Delta {U_{f}^{\circ }}_{\mathrm {reactants} }$ , the internal energy of formation of the reactant molecules, and $\Delta {U_{f}^{\circ }}_{\mathrm {products} }$ , the internal energy of formation of the product molecules.
[src:chemical-energy/chemical-energy] The internal energy change of a chemical process is equal to the heat exchanged if it is measured under conditions of constant volume and equal initial and final temperature, as in a closed container such as a bomb calorimeter.
[src:chemical-energy/chemical-energy] However, under conditions of constant pressure, as in reactions in vessels open to the atmosphere, the measured heat change is not always equal to the internal energy change, because pressure-volume work also releases or absorbs energy.
[src:chemical-energy/chemical-energy] (The heat change at constant pressure is equal to the enthalpy change, in this case the enthalpy of reaction, if initial and final temperatures are equal).
[src:chemical-energy/chemical-energy] A related term is the heat of combustion, which is the energy mostly of the weak double bonds of molecular oxygen released due to a combustion reaction and often applied in the study of fuels.
[src:chemical-energy/chemical-energy] Food is similar to hydrocarbon and carbohydrate fuels, and when it is oxidized to carbon dioxide and water, the energy released is analogous to the heat of combustion (though assessed differently than for a hydrocarbon fuel—see food energy).
[src:chemical-energy/chemical-energy] Chemical potential energy is a form of potential energy related to the structural arrangement of atoms or molecules.
[src:chemical-energy/chemical-energy] This arrangement may be the result of chemical bonds within a molecule or interactions between them.
[src:chemical-energy/chemical-energy] Chemical energy of a chemical substance can be transformed to other forms of energy by a chemical reaction.
[src:chemical-energy/chemical-energy] For example, when a fuel is burned, the chemical energy of molecular oxygen and the fuel is converted to heat.
[src:chemical-energy/chemical-energy] Green plants transform solar energy to chemical energy (mostly of oxygen) through the process of photosynthesis, and electrical energy can be converted to chemical energy and vice versa through electrochemical reactions.
[src:chemical-energy/chemical-energy] The similar term chemical potential is used to indicate the potential of a substance to undergo a change of configuration, be it in the form of a chemical reaction, spatial transport, particle exchange with a reservoir, etc.
[src:chemical-energy/chemical-energy] It is *not* a form of potential energy itself, but is more closely related to free energy.
